<DOCNO> XIE19970327.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Factory Orders for Durable Goods Up in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Orders to U.S. factories for
durable goods rose by 1.5 percent to a record level in February,
the U.S. Commerce Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The department said that orders for durable goods, items
expected to last for more than three years, rose to a seasonally
adjusted 178.3 billion dollars resulting from increasing demand
for communications and other electronic equipment.
</P>
<P>
The report said orders for electronic equipment rose by 7.4
percent in February on top of a 17.9 percent gain in the month
before. Orders climbed 2.2 percent for industrial machinery, the
third consecutive increase.
</P>
<P>
However, the often volatile transportation category fell 3.6
percent, with decreases in all components except railroads.
Primary metals such as steel edged 0.5 percent lower, the first
decline since October.
</P>
<P>
Overall, unfilled orders rose 1.1 percent, the ninth increase
in 10 months. A growing backlog of orders suggests manufacturers
will have to increase production and manpower to meet demand.
</P>
<P>
Orders for durable goods are a key barometer of the
manufacturing strength in the country. Today's report contributed
to economists' belief that the U.S. economy is growing briskly in
the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Federal Reserve raised the short-term interest rate
Tuesday by a quarter of a percentage point to curb the inflation
at a time when the economy is expanding more quickly than
expected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
