<DOCNO> XIE19970327.0004 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNG PM to Stand Aside </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Papua New Guinea Prime Minister
Julius Chan decided to stand aside under the increasing pressure
mounted over his secret deal to use mercenaries on Bougainville.
</P>
<P>
Julius announced his decision to a special meeting of
parliament this afternoon after parliament rejected a motion
calling for him to step down yesterday.
</P>
<P>
But parliament's rejection sparked strong reaction from
thousands of people and soldiers who were waiting outside the
parliament house. They started stoning cars and blocking entrances
to parliament all the night.
</P>
<P>
In his 20 minute statement, Julius said he would direct his
Deputy Prime Minister Chris Haiveta and Defense Minister Mathias
Ijape to step down with him.
</P>
<P>
All three were reported to have shared responsibility for the
Sandline deal, in which the government secretly arranged to spend
38 million US dollars to hire mercenaries to fight on the troubled
island of Bougainville.
</P>
<P>
As his statement was relayed outside parliament, a crowd of
about 2000 people cheered and some chanted "Singirok, Singirok" to
honor sacked defense chief Jerry Singirok who sparked the crisis
last week with a call for Julius to resign.
</P>
<P>
Julius also said he would push for national elections scheduled
for June to be brought forward.
</P>
<P>
Julius, 57, is an experienced politician in PNG. He has twice
become prime minister, and the first time was in 1980.  
</P>
</TEXT>
