<HEADLINE> Chinese, French Environmental Protection Heads Hold Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Director of China's State Bureau
of Environmental Protection Xie Zhenhua held talks with French
Minister of the Environment Corinne Lepage here today.
</P>
<P>
During the two-hour meeting, the two sides exchanged views on
global environmental protection, and discussed environmental
cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Xie briefed the guest on the measures China has taken and the
progress it has made in environmental protection. He said that
China has launched a large-scale combat against pollution, and it
will increase funding, strengthen the legal system, and rigorously
enforce environmental laws and regulations during the 1996-2000
period.
</P>
<P>
France has scored many achievements in environmental
protection, and has much experience in the field, Xie noted,
adding that China and France have a vast range of prospects in
environmental cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Xie expressed his hope that Lepage's visit will deepen the
understanding between the two sides, and push the two countries'
cooperation in environmental protection onto a new level.
</P>
<P>
He said that China has opened its doors in the area of
environmental protection and that he hopes France, with its
experience and advanced technology in environmental protection,
will enhance practical cooperation with China, such as in
environmental technology, legislation, and industry.
</P>
<P>
Lepage expressed great interest in China's environmental
protection work. She said that France is willing to cooperate with
China and that the aim of her visit is to give a push to the two
countries' cooperation in economy and technology, making it more
smooth and efficient.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the two sides reached consensus on the main
content of a draft agreement on Sino-French environmental
cooperation, and suggested to sign the agreement this May when
French President Jacques Rene Chirac visits China.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the meeting, the two sides signed a summary of
talks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
