<HEADLINE> Russian Cabinet Reorganization Finished </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Russia's government reshuffle
ended today after a string of new appointments over the last two
weeks aimed at boosting the economy and the government's
popularity.
</P>
<P>
President Boris Yeltsin met Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin
and other senior cabinet members in the Kremlin and signed a
number of decrees on appointments to the remaining vacant posts in
the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Former Economics Minister Yevgeny Yasin, seen as a leading
light in many of Russia's economic reforms, was appointed minister
without portfolio.
</P>
<P>
But Chernomyrdin told a press conference Yasin would coordinate
and review government policy and deal with economic questions.
</P>
<P>
Anatoly Chubais, appointed First Deputy Prime Minister last
week, was also given responsibility for issues associated with the
mass media. Former First Deputy Minister Mikhail Fradkov will
temporarily head the Ministry for Foreign Economic Relations and
Trade, Chernomyrdin announced.
</P>
<P>
Former Deputy Communications Minister Alexander Krupnov has
been appointed head of the State Committee for Communications and
Information in the new cabinet, the premier said.
</P>
<P>
President Yeltsin, back in command after months of illness,
ordered the wide-ranging cabinet reshuffle in an attempt to get
the economy going and solve many of the problems which have made
the government unpopular.
</P>
<P>
Wage and pension arrears nationwide are running at about 9
billion U.S. dollars and strikes have become commonplace as
workers protest against the nonpayment of wages. In February,
5,360 factories were affected by strike action. 
</P>
</TEXT>
