<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Great Potential for Malaysia-China Economic Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 26 (Xinhua) -- There exists great potential
for Malaysia and China to promote their economic cooperation as
China provides a vast market, Malaysian Deputy International Trade
and Industry Minister Kerk Choo Ting said here today.
</P>
<P>
China might become one of the largest economies in the world in
the near future, providing greater opportunities for businessmen
in Malaysia and other parts of the world, he said in an interview
with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Kerk said great achievements had already been made in recent
years in the economic cooperation between Malaysia and China,
which covers two aspects -- trade and investment.
</P>
<P>
At the moment, the two countries are trading in traditional
items, he said, adding "there exists greater potential for a boost
in bilateral trade, if both sides add more value-added, high-tech
products to the exchange lists while upgrading the traditional
ones."
</P>
<P>
As for mutual investment, he said Malaysian investors are
investing in areas such as tourism-related industries, palm oil
refinery, property market and infrastructure in China while
Chinese investors are investing in steel production, machinery
manufacturing and property market in Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Though the amount was comparatively small so far, property
market and the infrastructure sector in China have great potential
for Malaysian investors, he said.
</P>
<P>
The deputy minister said his government encouraged the private
sector to invest overseas in those areas where "we have
competitive advantages."
</P>
<P>
As Malaysia is concerned, he said "it is still a good place for
investment with attractive incentives, political and economic
stability, social harmony, environmental protection, low inflation
and legal framework."
</P>
<P>
Direct foreign investment in the country is "increasing from
year to year" and most attractive areas or sector for investment
in Malaysia are electric and electronics, petrochemicals,
technology, basic infrastructure and property market, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
