<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Seeks to Narrow Trade Gap With France </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 26 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government has
conveyed its desire to the French government to narrow down their
lopsided trade balance which remains in favor of Paris, the
Philippine News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Foreign Affairs Undersecretary Rodolfo Severino
formally conveyed Manila's position on the issue in the recently
concluded Second Philippine-France Sub-Ministerial Consultation
meeting in Manila.
</P>
<P>
Severino asked his French counterpart, Foreign Ministry
Secretary General Bertrand Dufouraq, to increase the level of
French investments in the country, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Severino noted that while French companies here lately showed
greater interest in investing in the country, the Philippines
still lags behind other ASEAN countries in terms of French trade
and investments.
</P>
<P>
French investments in the Philippines recently increased
dramatically with the participation of French Lyonnaise des Eaux
in the privatization of the Manila Waterworks and Sewerage
Authority.
</P>
<P>
Other French companies involved in major Philippine projects
include the BCEOM which will undertake the North Luzon Expressway
Extension to Subic; the Aerospatiale which will install the
Philippines' first satellite and Airbus Industries which is
involved in the massive refleeting program of the Philippine
Airlines (PAL).
</P>
<P>
PAL's refleeting program, which involves the acquisition of an
additional 36 new aircraft for the country's national carrier,
contributed the most to the trade imbalance between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Latest figures show that Philippine-French bilateral trade for
1996 reached 528.24 million US dollars. Of the total, French
export to the Philippines was 173.32 million US dollars in excess
of Manila export to Paris.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
