<HEADLINE> Togo Urges Concrete Measures to Stop Wars in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOME, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Togo's President Gnassingbe Eyadema
urged here today that African countries must take concrete
measures to stop wars in the African continent.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks at a grand opening ceremony for the first
extraordinary session of heads of state and government of the
Central Organ of the OAU Mechanism for Conflict Prevention,
Management and Resolution to seek a peaceful solution to the
Zaire crisis.
</P>
<P>
Eyadema said: "It is a must for us to take concrete measures
to stop the bleeding caused by wars which are weakening Africa,
breeding sentiments of hatred and are likely to lead to the
dismemberment of the Organization of African Unity."
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the special summit in quest of a solution to the
conflict in the Great Lakes region is "highly crucial for the
safeguard of the African unity", he noted.
</P>
<P>
He warned that the situation in the region is "seriously
alarming" and the devastations of the war in Zaire are likely to
"cause the implosion of the whole Africa".
</P>
<P>
"Our continent is faced with conflicts, disasters, threats and
refugee movements it never witnessed before", said the host
president.
</P>
<P>
But the time has come for Africa to take its destiny into its
own hands so that the OAU could efficiently apply the mechanism
for the prevention, the management and the settlements of
conflicts, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
"This extraordinary summit to seek solutions to the crisis in
the Great Lakes region is a big challenge that we must take up"
to demonstarte "our political political maturity and our genuine
willingness for peace", he said.
</P>
<P>
President Eyadema expressed his optimitism about a negotiated
settlement to the Zirean conflict, "because there is never a
problem without a solution".
</P>
<P>
He called on the conflicting parties in the Zaire crisis to
show a sense of goodwill so that a peaceful solution can be
found.
</P>
<P>
Fifteen African heads of state are attending the two-day
summit with 30 African countries and the two warring sides of
Zaire represented. OAU Secretary General Salim Ahamed Salim, UN
chief Koffi Annan and representatives of the United States,
Britain, France, Germany and the European Union are also present.
</P>
</TEXT>
