<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU, US Make Progress in Dispute over Helms-Burton Act </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Stuart Eizenstat, the U.S. special envoy on Cuba policy, and
Sir Leon Brittan, the EU trade commissioner, had four hours of
talks here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The talks were described as being constructive by senior
officials from both sides.
</P>
<P>
"We have a better understanding of each other's needs and
ideas," said Eizenstat. "There are still significant hurdles,
but progress has been made."
</P>
<P>
As a gesture of his "desire to continue intensive talks," Sir
Leon has agreed to send a group of officials from the European
Commission, the EU's executive body, to Washington for discussions
next week, a spokesman for the commission said.
</P>
<P>
Both sides have been making every effort to reach a settlement
before mid-April, when a WTO panel is scheduled to open hearings
into an EU complaint against the U.S. Helms-Burton Act which
sanctions a third country that does business in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. gave a vigorous reaction to the recent appointment by
the WTO of three panelists to hear the case. Eizenstat even
indicated that Washington would refuse to cooperate with the panel
by citing the rarely invoked national security clause in the rules
governing international trade.
</P>
<P>
However, neither the EU nor Washington want to see the threat
really carried out because it would pose a serious threat to the
credibility of the WTO, as one U.S. official admitted here
Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
