<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Mulls Plan to Solve Sugar Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
said today that the government is working out a program to resolve
the sugar price crisis which has plagued the country since last
October.
</P>
<P>
But Ramos refused to remove Wilson Gamboa, chief of the Sugar
Regulatory Administration (SRA), from his post as demanded by
sugarcane planters.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at his weekly press conference, Ramos said the sugar
crisis will not be resolved by "the removal of people."
</P>
<P>
Ramos promised to solve the problem facing the sugar industry
entirely by enhancing its competitiveness in the global market.
</P>
<P>
The country's sugar industry has been in a crisis after sugar
prices continued slumping since last October. Farmgate price per
bag (50 kg) of raw sugar plummeted from 900 pesos in February 1995
to less than 500 early this year, resulting in great economic
losses to sugar planters and millers.
</P>
<P>
The plunge in sugar prices was caused by a glut of sugar supply
in the domestic market due to over-importation of refined sugar
last year, according to the SRA.  
</P>
</TEXT>
