<HEADLINE> Mahathir, Hashimoto Agree on Regular ASEAN-Japan Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir
Mohamad and Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto agreed today
to hold regular summit talks between the Association of Southeast
Asian Nations (ASEAN) and Japan.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir expressed support for such summits in a 90-minute
meeting here, saying he and leaders of the six other ASEAN members
have welcomed the bid, the Japanese news agency Kyodo News said.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir, now on a four-day official visit through Friday, also
greeted Hashimoto's initiative for having ASEAN's voice in the
summit talks reflect in the discussions among the Group of Seven
(G-7) industrialized nations of which Japan is a member.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto, who proposed the summit talks during his five-nation
tour of the ASEAN in January, told Mahathir that he wants to see
various kinds of opportunities to establish closer relations
between Tokyo and the ASEAN by expanding bilateral dialogue.
</P>
<P>
On bilateral trade issues, Mahathir urged Tokyo to make further
efforts to redress the trade imbalance in Japan's favor, according
to the news agency.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir also agreed with Hashimoto on backing China's bid to
join the World Trade Organization. 
</P>
