<DOCNO> XIE19970327.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Refutes "Exploitation of Xinjiang" (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 26 (Xinhua) -- A State Planning Commission
spokesman refuted as "groundless" a report forwarded by the United
Nations Center for Human Rights which said the Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region has to turn in large amounts of petroleum and
grain to the central government.
</P>
<P>
According to a letter from the UN center, Xinjiang has to hand
in 80 million tons of petroleum and 40 million tons of grain to
the central government during the country's Ninth Five-Year Plan
(1996-2000) period.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman noted that for a long time the central government
has gone all out to support economic and social development in
areas inhabited by minority ethnic groups, and offered a series of
preferential treatment in their fiscal revenue and the arrangement
of investment projects there.
</P>
<P>
As one of China's five autonomous regions inhabited by national
minorities, the spokesman noted, economic and social development
in Xinjiang has always received great support from the central
government.
</P>
<P>
From 1991 to 1995, the region made use of an investment 66
billion yuan in its capital construction, with 55.9 billion yuan
from the state. The proportion of state investment in Xinjiang is
much higher than the country's average.
</P>
<P>
Last year, a total of 19.24 billion yuan of capital
construction investment went to Xinjiang, including 13.85 billion
from the state, suggesting a proportion much higher than that in
other places of the country.
</P>
<P>
Xinjiang's economy developed faster than ever during the
1990-95 period, the spokesman said, adding that the state will
continue arranging a great sum of investment into Xinjiang's
infrastructure construction.
</P>
<P>
According to the spokesman, the central government dispatched
at least 200,000 tons of grain to Xinjiang annually before
1985. With the backing of the central government after 1985,
Xinjiang developed very rapidly in its grain production and was
able to achieve grain self-sufficiency. Some places have even been
faced with the difficulty in grain sales.
</P>
<P>
To protect the interest of local farmers, the central budget
even allocated special funds to purchase the surplus grains that
the farmers were willing to sell at a price higher than market
price, and stored them on site as preparations for a bad year, the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, for instance, the central government issued orders of
purchasing 100,000 tons of wheat and 175,000 tons of corn for
storage right after a good harvest in Xinjiang, which protected
the interest of the farmers.
</P>
<P>
It is out of ulterior motives to distort such practices aimed
at protecting the interest of farmers into forcing Xinjiang to
offer grain to the central government, the spokesman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970327.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Refutes "Exploitation of Xinjiang" (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The spokesman pointed out that the country's support to the
region to exploit oil and gas is aimed at playing up local
resource advantages so as to promote economic and social
development in the region.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Xinjiang produced some 14 million tons of crude oil,
most of which was processed and used in the region. The processed
products first satisfied local needs for oil products and chemical
materials.
</P>
<P>
The remaining crude oil and processed oil products were sold in
 other places of the country to fulfill its commercial value.
</P>
<P>
Everyone with common economic sense should know that commodity
circulation can not be limited by natural or administrative
regions, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Xinjiang's selling a proportion of oil to other places was not
only a support to the whole country but also the needs of local
economic development, he said, adding that such regular market
economic activity was beyond reproach.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman told the reporter that every year the country
arranges help-the-poor funds to promote economic development in
poverty-stricken areas in the region.
</P>
<P>
This year, the country has allocated some 685 million yuan into
such funds. An amount of 3.5 billion yuan will go to Xinjiang in
the 1996-2000 period.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the country allocated another 600 million yuan for a
1995-97 project to improve drinking water facilities in rural
areas in Xinjiang.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman pointed out that for quite some time, some people
in the international community, in the name of protecting human
rights, have been maliciously attacking China and sowing
dissension among Chinese nationalities with fabricated and
distorted cases.
</P>
<P>
"Their plot will never succeed, " he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
