<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Opposes Partial Publication of Archives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 26 (Xinhua) -- France today expressed its wish
that the gold of Jews robbed by the Nazis during World War II will
be returned to their owners rapidly, but said it opposes "partial
publication" of the archives concerning this question.
</P>
<P>
"Our concern... is to return this gold in serenity and with
celebrity," French Foreign Ministry spokesman Jacques Rummelhardt
said.
</P>
<P>
He said that according to a tripartite commission on Nazi gold
set up in 1945 by Britain, the United States and France, out of
the 337 tons of Jewish gold robbed by Germany, the whereabout of
5.5 tons of the gold remained unknown.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Brussels-based tripartite commission should
now "work with serenity" in investigating the whereabout of the
gold.
</P>
<P>
"Rather than making partial publication of the archives of the
commission, we support the opening of these archives as soon as
the tripartite commission has done their work," he said.
</P>
<P>
The United States has asked for publication now of the
archives.
</P>
<P>
France has set up its own commission to investigate the
whereabout of Nazi gold in France and other Jewish properties
robbed during World War II in order to return them to their
original owners.
</P>
<P>
The World Jewish Congress and the Representative Council of
Jewish Institutions in France have asked the members of the
tripartite commission, in particular France, to investigate the
whereabout of the gold, part of which is now reportedly stocked in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that a solution that complies with the law and equity
will be elaborated," said the spokesman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
