<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Peace Broker Leaves for Mideast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 26 (Xinhua) -- The Clinton administration
today dispatched its chief Middle East peace broker Dennis Ross to
Morocco for talks with Palestinian President Yasser Arafat to halt
violence triggered by Israelis breaking ground for Jewish housing
construction in east Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Ross' mission is to stop strong Palestinian opposition, which
might evolve into violence, to obvious violations by the Israeli
government of Israeli-Palestinian agreements.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli government, defying worldwide criticism of its
decision to build 6,500 Jewish homes in traditionally Arab east
Jerusalem, has vowed to push forward with its construction plans.
</P>
<P>
The United States, placating the Palestinians with some oral
criticism of the Israeli decision, has twice vetoed U.N. Security
Council resolutions condemning Isreal's construction decision.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright wrote
a letter to Arafat urging him to refrain Palestinians from taking
any violent actions against Israelis, tantamount to say the
Palestinians should sit by to watch Israelis doing whatever they
like in defiance of any peace agreements.
</P>
<P>
It was said Ross will seek, first of all, a clear statement
from Arafat to halt attacks on Israelis.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, a suicide bomber killed three women in a Tel Aviv
cafe and injured scores of others.
</P>
<P>
Ross will first meet Arafat in Rabat, Morocco, then fly to
Israel to urge Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu to ease
tensions. He will try to persuade Arafat and Netanyahu to open
negotiations over the future of the West Bank and Jerusalem.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
