<DOCNO> XIE19970327.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiang Confers with Gore on Principles Guiding Sino-US Ties (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Reviewing the growth of Sino-US relations in the past 25 years,
Jiang said that despite twists and turns, Sino-US ties as a whole
have scored relatively great expansion on the basis of three
Sino-US joint communiques.
</P>
<P>
With joint efforts of both sides, the two countries have
achieved some positive progress in their relations in recent
years, and they are facing chances for further improvement and
development, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, there still exist some problems and difficulties which
need to be dealt with appropriately, and some new interferences
and hindrances are yet to be removed, he said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his conviction that as long as they proceed from
the fundamental interests of the peoples in the two countries and
from the overall situation of safeguarding world peace, the two
sides can dispel all interferences and Sino-US relations will
maintain long-term stability and development
</P>
<P>
Gore said he took joy in his two-day visit and was pleased with
a wide range of talks with Premier Li Peng and other Chinese
leaders over the past two days.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that the talks had enhanced his belief that
the US and China must increase cooperation in bilateral relations
and on regional and international issues, and they should have
frequent contacts at varying levels, increase their exchanges, and
expand their common understanding.
</P>
<P>
Also participating in today's meeting were Chen Jinhua,
minister in charge of the State Planning Commission, Liu Huaqiu,
director of the Foreign Affairs Office under the State Council, Li
Daoyu, Chinese Ambassador to the US, and Li Zhaoxing, Chinese
vice-foreign minister, and James Sasser, US Ambassador to China.
</P>
</TEXT>
