<HEADLINE> S. Africa, Mozambique Sign Landmines Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 26 (Xinhua) -- South Africa and Mozambique
signed an agreement today, confirming both sides's commitment to a ban
on anti-personnel landmines.
</P>
<P>
South African Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo and his Mozambican
counterpart Leonardo signed the agreement in Lome, Togo,
according to the South African Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, both South Africa and Mozambique will ban
the use of anti-personnel landmines in their respective countries.
</P>
<P>
It could be regarded as "another watershed event" in the
relations between South Africa and Mozambique, the ministry
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
With the announcement of banning anti-personnel landmines, the
two countries affirmed their parntership in the campaign for
a mine-free southern Africa and in the international campaign to
ban landmines, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
According to the South African Press Association (SAPA), about
two million landmines had been scattered in Mozambique, posing
the biggest threat to the reconstruction and development underway
in that country.
</P>
<P>
Lifting the mines in Mozambique was of mutual benefit, but in
particular it would help Mozambican citizens stimulate the
important agricultural sector, SAPA said. enditem

