<DOCNO> XIE19970327.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Chief Urges Zairean Warring Sides to Cease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOME, March 26 (Xinhua) -- UN Secretary-General Koffi Annan
today appealed to the warring parties of Zaire to cease fire and
"move to the negotiating table" to solve their conflict.
</P>
<P>
He made the appeal in his speech at the special summit of the
Organization of African Unity on the Zaire crisis, which was
opened here today.
</P>
<P>
He said that he strongly endorses the call of the Nairobi
Summit II that the warring parties should cease hostilities and
create the necessary environment to facilitate a negotiated
settlement to the Zaire crisis.
</P>
<P>
The UN chief arrived at the capital of Togo from Angola
yesterday to attend the two-day summit, at which 30 African
countries are represented.
</P>
<P>
Annan stressed that Zaire and its people must move forward on a
clear path towards lasting peace and reconstruction based on
democracy, the rule of law and respect for human rights.
</P>
<P>
"But before that can happen, the fighting must stop and a
dialogue must begin among Zaireans," he said.
</P>
<P>
He stated that the United Nations will continue to press the
two sides so that they, "without further delay", accept total
cessation of hostilities and commence negotiations.
</P>
<P>
But the secretary general noted that effective peace-making
and conflict resolution in the Great Lakes region must embrace the
broadest humanitarian, social and economic dimensions, because
military might or intevention alone cannot successfully lay the
fountations for lasting peace.
</P>
<P>
At the end of his speech, he asked Africans not to shelter
behind narrow nationalism because the sufferings of any African
affect all Africans.
</P>
<P>
Annan said that "African unity is the key" as Africa does not
command great arsenals. "But African unity can be a strong moral
force. When Africa speaks with one voice, the world listens," he
added.
</P>
<P>
The summit, chaired by President of Cameroun Paul Biya who is also
chairman of the OAU, will focus its discussions on what a mechanism
should be established to ensure the implementation of a five-point
peace plan in the war-torn Zaire.
</P>
<P>
Zairean President Mobutu Sese Seko's delegation, which is led by
Vice President of parliament Boboliko, and a two-member delegation of
rebel leader Laurent Kabila are in the Togolese capital for the
summit.
</P>
<P>
The African leaders are now holding closed-door meetings and
will issue a communique at the end of the summit tomorrow.
</P>
</TEXT>
