<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Turns Tough on Sending Back Bosnian Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Interior ministers from Germany's 16
federal states today decided to carry on the implementation of a
plan to send back Bosnian refugees living in the country.
</P>
<P>
Up from May 1, Germany will repatriate not only single people,
childless couples and Bosnians with a criminal record in Germany,
but also those refugees with families, thus starting the so-called
second phase of the repatriation plan, ministers said.
</P>
<P>
Those refugees who are receiving medical treatment in Germany,
or students who began their education in Germany before January
26, 1996 are allowed to stay in the country temporarily. Bosnian
refugees who plan to move to the United States, Canada or
Australia from Germany are also allowed to stay until their
departure.
</P>
<P>
The decision followed the deportation of 41 Bosnian refugees
Tuesday, which was the first relatively large-scale repatriation
of Bosnian refugees from Germany this year.
</P>
<P>
Uneasy with the heavy financial burden of hosting refugees,
estimated at 3 billion U.S. dollars a year, German local
authorities have mounted increasing pressure on the 320,000
predominantly Muslim Bosnian war refugees living in the country to
return home voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
The authorities have cut some social security payments and
insisted that the overall Bosnian refugee population in Germany be
reduced by some 80,000 before summer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
