<HEADLINE> S.Africa Sells 30 Percent of State-owned Telkom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 26 (Xinhua) -- The South African government
today signed an agreement to sell 30 percent equity stake of
state-owned telecommunication corporation Telkom to two foreign
consortium, the United States-based SBC International and Telkom
Malaysia Berhard.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference in Midrand, north of Johannesburg, Posts,
Telecommunications and Broadcasting Minister Jay Naidoo said the 1.26
billion US Dollar deal represented the single largest direct foreign
investment in South Africa to date and the beginning of the
implementation of the government's restructuring program for
state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the injection of foreign currency to the country's
reserves, Telkom would also be committed to 53 billion Rand (about
11.7 billion US Dollar) capital expenditure over the next five-year
period, almost doubling the current program, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
The deal would probably provide a significant boost to the South
African economy and a creation of 50,000 new jobs, both in
telecommunications and supporting industries.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, SBC International and Telkom Malaysia Berhard promised
to install 2.7 million new telephone lines and 120,000 pay phones over
the next five-year period.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Deputy President Thabo Mbeki also announced that the
government would inject one billion US Dollar into Telkom to help fund
the infrastructure expansion program. enditem

