<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-26 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinian Official Hopes Ross' Mission to Solve </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 26 (Xinhua) -- As U.S. Middle East peace envoy
Dennis Ross is returning to the Middle East on a rescue mission,
a senior Palestinian official expressed the hope today that the
U.S. intervention could solve the current crisis on the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Abu Ala (or Ahmed Queria), Speaker of the Palestinian
Council (PC), was quoted by Israel Radio as saying that either
the U.S. direct intervention or the international arbitration
could solve the deepening crisis between Israel and the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA).
</P>
<P>
But he stressed that the ball was in Israel's court, and
the Israeli government had to decide whether it wanted to
continue the peace process or not.
</P>
<P>
Ross is expected to travel to Rabat, capital of Morocco,
Thursday, where he will hold a meeting with PNA President Yasser
Arafat who has decided to cut short his current Asian tour in
order to meet Ross.
</P>
<P>
After meeting with Arafat, Ross will fly on to Israel to
hold talks with Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu. Then
he will go back to Washington Friday to report to President
Bill Clinton the results of the meetings.
</P>
<P>
Ross is facing a tougher task this time in his attempt to
restart the stalled Israeli-Palestinian peace negotiations
because of the wide gap between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, both sides have been critical of the U.S. stance on
the ongoing crisis.
</P>
<P>
Israel has demanded the PNA clearly renounce what it called
"the tactics of violence" and strengthen its crackdown on
extremism, while the PNA insisted on Israel's suspension of
settlement activities, especially the construction on Har Homa
of southeastern Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Although the U.S. criticized Israel for making the Har Homa
settlement decision, it nevertheless vetoed a United Nations
Security Council draft resolution which urged the Jewish state to
abandon the Har Homa project. Israel rejected the U.S. criticism
and went ahead with the Har Homa construction last week.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian side at the same time denounced the U.S. veto
of the U.N. resolution as an act of encouraging Israel to build
the settlement in East Jerusalem before the final-status talks
begin. In recent demonstrations, Palestinian protesters poured out
their anger by burning both Israeli and the U.S. flags.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a war of words between Israeli and Palestinian
officials continued today, with both accusing each other of
violating the peace accords and jeopardizing the peace process.
</P>
<P>
David Bar-Illan, media adviser to Netanyahu, slammed Arafat
for playing the card of terrorism in dealing with Israel.
</P>
<P>
On the question regarding the peace march, he said, "I can
promise that it will not work this time. This government has made
it very clear that it will not work. We will not tolerate
violence, we will not see violence as part of the peace process."
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Ross' mediation tour, Bar-Illan said Israel
hoped him to relay a clear message to Arafat that he should make
a decision "once for all" to renounce violence and solve all
differences through negotiations.
</P>
<P>
In his counter-charges, Chief Palestinian Negotiator Saeb
Erekat warned that Israel's moves to expand settlements were
threatening to kill the peace march.
</P>
<P>
He insisted that it was the Israeli government that had incited
the recent wave of violence by going ahead with the Har Homa
project in defiance of widespread condemnations and warnings of
violence.
</P>
<P>
Erekat, critical of the U.S. partial stance favoring Israeli in
mediating the peace process, hoped that Ross would persuade the
Netanyahu government to stop settlement activities and come back
to the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
He added that Ross should concentrate his efforts on the
substance of the peace process instead of only bringing
the talks on track. He warned that "the idea of peace is dying
away" because of Israel's refusal to implement precisely and
honestly the peace agreements. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
