<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Toyota to Sell Low Emission Car </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Toyota, the leading auto maker
of Japan, is to introduce a hybrid electric-and-gasoline power
system for cars that it says doubles fuel efficiency and cuts
emissions 90 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to a report of the Wall Street Journal today, the
system combines a gasoline engine, an electric motor and
nickel-metal hydride battery on a single power train. The gasoline
engine supplies the main power to drive the wheels. But the
electric battery and electric generator can also power the
electric motor. The hybrid system will go on sale in Japan this
year, it said.
</P>
<P>
A number of auto makers have been experimenting with them, the
paper said, and a few years ago, Ford Motor Co. had a test fleet
of hybrid-powered vans operating in California.
</P>
<P>
It also reported that the Audi AG unit of Germany's Volkswagen
AG has also developed hybrid power systems.
</P>
<P>
Toyota said it will aim the hybrid system at the mass market.
Its success will depend in large part on the price, still
unannounced. It appears to have resolved other major barriers
impeding the wide use of low-emission vehicles: short battery
life and limited power.
</P>
<P>
The electric battery in the hybrid won't ever need special
recharging under normal circumstances.
</P>
<P>
The first hybrid car will have a 1.5-liter engine, about the
size of the engine in the Toyota Corolla. But the company said
the car will run about twice as far on a tank of gas as the
Corolla, which gets about 18 miles a gallon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
