<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-26 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1-Billion-Dollar Petrochemical Complex to Be </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TABRIZ, IRAN, March 26 (Xinhua) -- A 1-billion-dollar
petrochemical complex in Iran will soon be put into operation with
the help of France, Italy, Germany, Japan and South Korea despite
a U.S. embargo.
</P>
<P>
Abbas Sedghi, Managing Director of the Tabriz Petrochemical
Complex (TPC), told a group of foreign reporters here today that
all the equipment of the complex has not been covered by the
U.S. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton signed the D' Amato Law last
August to impose sanctions against oil companies to invest
annually 40 million U.S. dollars or more in Iran and Libya, which
are regarded by the U.S. as countries supporting terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The director said that the TPC is the third largest
petrochemical plant in the country after the Bandar Iman
(Khomeini) Complex at the Gulf and the Arak Complex in central
Iran.
</P>
<P>
With an annual capacity of 500,000 tonnes of different
polymers, he said, the TPC is the second plant in the Middle
East to manufacture expandable polystyrene. The other one is in
Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
"The main objective for setting up the TPC is expected to
produce various petrochemical products, including more than
300,000 tonnes of polystyrene and polyethylene substances,
applied industrial parts as well as household appliances as
plastic covers," he said.
</P>
<P>
The project, which started in 1989 and is to be inaugurated
soon by President Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani, has a budget of 1
billion dollars and a large sum of local currency.
</P>
<P>
The output of the complex is initially used for domestic
consumption but may later even reach the export level, the
director said, adding that the TPC will drastically increase the
supply and decrease the need for petrochemical imports.
</P>
<P>
Sedghi noted that the work on the TPC was mainly by Iranian
experts with the cooperation of foreign firms from Belgium,
Britain, France, Germany, Italy, the Netherlands, Spain and South
Korea, which were mainly in charge of design and provision of
related equipment.
</P>
<P>
Iran, the fourth largest oil producer and second largest oil
exporter in the world, pumps out 3.6 million barrels per day
(bpd) and exports 2.5 million bpd.
</P>
<P>
Iran has 16 petrochemical plants with an annual capacity of 11
million tonnes of various products, which bring about about 500
million dollars to the country.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian Oil Ministry predicted that Iran would export 14
million tonnes of petrochemical products by the turn of the
century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
