<HEADLINE> Sinn Fein to Play Constructive Role, Says CBI </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 26 (Xinhua) -- The Confederation of British
Industry (CBI) and the Irish Republic Army's political wing Sinn
Fein have recently met to discuss political and economic issues.
</P>
<P>
The CBI defended its decision to meet Sinn Fein officials,
claiming they represented a significant proportion of the
population in Northern Ireland and that the meeting was part of a
discussion of the province's political and economic problems.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the two parties met several times during
the IRA cease-fire and at least once since the collapse of the
cease-fire in February 1996.
</P>
<P>
Bill Tosh of the Northern Ireland CBI said in a TV interview
that Sinn Fein had a good insight into some of the problems
affecting some communities in Northern Ireland and that it had a
constructive role to play in economic regeneration.
</P>
<P>
He dismissed claims that the CBI should not talk with Sinn Fein
and denied their political role led directly to Northern Ireland's
economic problems.
</P>
<P>
Tosh said issues such as long-term unemployment and the
economic regeneration of inner cities and deprived rural areas
were discussed, as well as the current political situation and the
general election.
</P>
<P>
Mitchel McLaughlin, Sinn Fein's chairman, said the party had
been involved in a "useful and constructive exchange" with the CBI
and they had also been able to give their own opinion of the
political situation.
</P>
<P>
"Our discussions centered on a number of issues, including the
growth challenge, inward investment and unemployment," he added.
</P>
<P>
Caoimhghin O'Caolin, a member of the Sinn Fein, who was at the
meeting said, "We looked in particular at how disadvantaged areas,
like the border counties, could be regenerated." 
</P>
</TEXT>
