<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-26 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German FM: Turkey's Bid for EU Not to Be Rejected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 26 (Xinhua) -- German Foreign Minister Klaus
Kinkel said here today that Turkey's bid for joining the
European Union (EU) would not be rejected, but Ankara will
have to wait for the club membership.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel, who arrived here late Wednesday night for a two-day
visit, made the remarks this afternoon at a joint press
conference with his Turkish counterpart Tansu Ciller following
their official talks.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel, also deputy prime minister, said: "The Turkish train
remains on the main track, it will not be put on the side track".
But he ruled out the possibility of Turkey's accession into the EU
in the short term.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has a series of problems to be sorted out before being
admitted into the EU, said Kinkel, adding: "Turkey will not be
able to become a member of the European Union in the near future
due to human rights, Kurdish issue, dispute with Greece and some
economic questions."
</P>
<P>
Ankara vowed to veto the NATO expansion process if its
full EU membership bid failed, claiming that the two processes
were directly linked, which was termed as "blackmail" by
Germany.
</P>
<P>
Turkey was greatly angered by a March 4 statement by the
EU Christian Democrats who called Turkey's membership application
unacceptable due to its religious culture.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel was close to calling off his visit at last minute
because of media reports quoting Turkish Islamist Prime Minister
Necmettin Erbakan as saying that he should come to Turkey with
his head bowed.
</P>
<P>
The German foreign minister, accompanied by a 75-member
delegation including businessmen, press, officials and
parliamentarians, postponed his visit to Ankara for two hours.
</P>
<P>
"No European will have to bow their head to Turkey in
shame, " Kinkel told the press on the first day of an
official visit to Turkey.
</P>
<P>
However, before meeting with Kinkel today, Erbakan said that
the gathering of the representatives from the two countries is a
satisfying event, adding: "the development of the bilateral ties
between Turkey and Germany not only attaches great importance to
the peace in Europe, but also to the world peace."
</P>
<P>
Before meeting the members of the Foreign Relations Commission
of the Turkish parliament, Kinkel said that Turkey's relations
with Europe should be maintained in a calm atmosphere and over 2
million Turkish citizens living in Germany contributed a lot to
the German economy.
</P>
<P>
German businessmen in the delegation are expected to hold
contacts with Turkish private sector representatives and
ministries responsible for economic and technical issues in
addition to seeking for cooperation facilities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
