<HEADLINE> Togo Urges Concrete Measures to Stop Wars in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOME, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Togolese President Gnassingbe
Eyadema said here today that African countries must take concrete
measures to stop wars which are afflicting their poor continent.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks at a grand opening ceremony for the first
extraordinary session of heads of states and government of the
Central Organ of the Organization of African Unity (OAU)
Mechanism for Conflict Prevention, Management and Resolution to
seek a peaceful solution to the Zairean crisis.
</P>
<P>
"It is a must for us to take concrete measures to stop the
bleeding caused by wars which are weakening Africa, breeding
sentiments of hatred and are likely to lead to the dismemberment
of the Organization of African Unity," said Eyadema.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the special summit for the quest of solution to the
conflict which is tearing the Great Lakes region is "highly
crucial for the safeguard of the African unity", he noted in his
speech.
</P>
<P>
The Togolese president warned that the situation in the region
is "seriously alarming" and the devastations of war in eastern
Zaire are likely to "cause the explosion of the whole Africa."
</P>
<P>
"Our continent is faced with conflicts, disasters, threats and
refugee movements it never witnessed before," he said.
</P>
<P>
But the time has come for Africa to take its destiny into its
own hands so that the OAU could efficiently apply the mechanism
for the prevention, management and settlement of conflicts, he
stressed.
</P>
<P>
"This extraordinary summit to seek solutions to the crisis in
the Great Lakes region is a big challenge that we must take up"
to demonstrate "our political maturity and our genuine
willingness for peace," he said.
</P>
<P>
President Eyadema expressed his optimism about a negotiated
settlement to the Zairean conflict, "because there is never a
problem without a solution."
</P>
<P>
He called on the conflicting parties to show a sense of good
will so that in forgiveness, tolerance and reconciliation, a
peaceful solution can be found.
</P>
<P>
Fifteen African heads of state are attending the two-day
summit with 30 African countries and two warring sides of Zaire
represented. OAU Secretary-General Salim Ahmed Salim, United
Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan and representatives of the
United States, Britain, France, Germany and the European Union
were also present. 
</P>
</TEXT>
