<HEADLINE> Ban On Use Of DDT Reiterated In Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 26 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzania Government
has reiterated that the DDT pesticide is banned and that anyone
found formulating, manufacturing or using it will face court
charges.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Agriculture and Livestock, Paul Kimiti, made the
remarks here today when opening a one-day workshop on pesticides
law in Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
According to the existing pesticide laws which are governed by
the Tropical Pesticides Research Institute (TPRI) Act of 1979 and
subsequent pesticide control regulations of 1984, anyone
convicted of violating the laws is liable to a fine of 3,000
Tanzanian Shillings or three months of imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
DDT is still rampantly used in Morogoro, Kilimanjaro and other
regions despite the ban and relevant health implications.
</P>
<P>
About 50 journalists, environmentalists, lawyers and chemical
experts attended the meeting. Enitem

