<HEADLINE> Pesticide Distribution Insufficient, Irregular in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, March 26 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Agriculture
of Ethiopia announced here today that pesticides are not reaching
farmers in sufficient amounts and the ministry is contacting
importers and distributors to look for solution to the problem.
</P>
<P>
According to a report from the Ethiopian News Agency, Baten
Kabeto, head of Agricultural Development and Crop Protection
Department in the ministry, said shortage of pesticides and weed
killers is prevalent currently in most rural areas throughout the
country owing to irregularities in the supply and distribution of
the chemicals.
</P>
<P>
He said importers and distributors of pesticides do not
directly provide services to rural areas and their activities are
confined to capital Addis Ababa and some other urban centers
alone.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Agriculture was discussing the issue with
entrepreneurs engaged in the sector with a view to making farmers
in all areas beneficiaries of pesticides and weed killer
supplies, he added.
</P>
<P>
According to an earlier report, the ministry said last week
that the country had the capacity to ward off any resurgency of
pest, with 225,000 liters of pesticides distributed by the
central government and 458,000 liters stored by regions.
</P>
<P>
There are 26 importers of pesticides and weed killers
operating in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
