<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Leaders Call for Peace With One Voice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOME, March 26 (Xinhua) -- African leaders, gathering in the
Togolese capital for the first extraordinary summit of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) on the escalating Zairean
conflict, today called, with one voice, for peace in their
continent.
</P>
<P>
At the opening ceremony held here today, five African leaders
who made their speeches all urged the Zaire's warring sides to
stop fighting immediately and to begin negotiations so that a
lasting peace will be brought back to their countries.
</P>
<P>
In his opening speech, President of Cameroun Paul Biya who is
also chairman of the OAU said African countries attach great
importance to peace in Africa and peaceful solutions to all
conflicts within the continent.
</P>
<P>
However, the peace is dangerously threatened by the crisis in
the Great Lakes region, particularly in eastern Zaire, he noted,
adding that an immediate ceasefire and direct and frank talks are
urgently needed for peace in the region and Africa as a whole.
</P>
<P>
He hoped the summit will find a way acceptable to both sides
for the implementation of the UN/OAU five-point peace plan.
</P>
<P>
The current OAU chairman also proposed that an international
conference be held to seek a complete and effective way for
resolving the conflict in Zaire.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, President Gnassingbe Eyadema of Togo warned that
the situation in the Great Lakes region is "seriously alarming"
and the devastations of war in eastern Zaire are likely to "cause
the explosion of the whole Africa."
</P>
<P>
The president stressed that African countries must take
"concrete measures to stop wars" which are afflicting their poor
continent.
</P>
<P>
He said:" Violence breeds violence and the escalation of
violence leads to war. War kills. War destroys. War is deadly
madness"
</P>
<P>
African countries, which are already in war against poverty,
must avoid to indulge in another war, that is the ethnic war
which is more suicidal and more deadly, he appealed.
</P>
<P>
Once more, Kenyan President Denial arap Moi reiterated the
call for a ceasefire and negotiated settlement made by the
Nairobi peace process for Zaire since the start of civil war in
Zaire, the third largest country in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The summit will provide a chance to seek a peaceful solution
to the conflict in Zaire, but it is also a real challenge, OAU
chief Salim Ahmed Salim pointed out.
</P>
<P>
However, he reaffirmed that OAU is totally committed to the
unity, stability, security and territorial integrity of Zaire.
</P>
<P>
Koffi Annan, United Nations Secretary-General who arrived here
yesterday from Angola to attend the summit, declared that the UN
will continue to press the two warring sides of Zaire in order
that, "without further delay", they accept total cessation of
hostilities and commence negotiations.
</P>
<P>
On the same occasion, he called for African unity which he
said "is the key and can be strong moral force".
</P>
<P>
"When Africa speaks with one voice, the world listens. But if
Africa speaks with a cacophony of confused messages, few will
listen, and no one will hear," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
