<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CBI Anger With Labor's "Underhand" Action </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 26 (Xinhua) -- The British opposition party
Labor's efforts to show a business-friendly image were under
severe strain since the Confederation of British Industry (CBI)
described it as acting in an "underhand" way Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
The row followed a disarray over Labor's plans to give unions
new recognition rights, with a judge appointed to resolve disputes
with employers.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Adair Turner, the CBI director general,
had told his colleagues that he felt "used" by the Labor Party,
which had acted in an "underhand" way by suggesting that he was a
party to its business manifesto.
</P>
<P>
Turner was "unhappy" with the way Labor has portrayed his
involvement and the implication that he has endorsed the business
manifesto, particularly as he disagreed with the section on union
recognition.
</P>
<P>
Interviewed on BBC Television's On the Record program Sunday,
Gordon Brown, the shadow chancellor, repeatedly emphasized that
the party's plans for business had been discussed with Turner.
</P>
<P>
Brown claimed that Turner was "happy on behalf of the CBI" to
join a working party Labor planned to set up in government to
discuss European Union policies affecting business.
</P>
<P>
Labor's document, he said, would "reflect two years of very
intense discussion with business about the way ahead."
</P>
<P>
A spokesman from the CBI said the employers' organization had
not yet agreed to join the working party but would be "interested"
in seeing what a Labor government proposed.
</P>
<P>
"On the manifesto itself, we were in no way involved with it
and its production," he added.
</P>
<P>
Turner issued a statement Tuesday night confirming that reports
of the CBI's involvement in the Labor business manifesto had been
exaggerated and that it had seen just one paragraph. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
