<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qatar, Oman Threaten to Sever Ties with Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Qatar and Oman threatened to
break relations with Israel if the Jewish state does not give up
its policy on building a new settlement in East Jerusalem, foreign
ministers of the two countries said in the Saudi capital of
Riyadh today.
</P>
<P>
Qatari Foreign Minister Sheikh Hamad Ben Jassem Bin Jaber
al-Thani told reporters that his country "would not hesitate in
severing its relations with Israel if the government of Prime
Minister Binyamin Netanyahu continues its stubborn policy."
</P>
<P>
He said "Qatar is an Arab (country) and a GCC member state and
if Israel continues its stubborn policy we would take whatever
necessary (steps) to help our Palestinian and Syrian brothers
without hesitation."
</P>
<P>
But Sheikh Hamad also said that despite the possible
suspension of ties with Israel, his country still hopes that the
United States will succeed in changing Israel's decision
concerning the settlement.
</P>
<P>
Omani State Minister for Foreign Affairs Yusef Ben Alawi Bin
Abdallah also threatened earlier day to totally sever relations
with Israel unless Netanyahu changes his policy.
</P>
<P>
Qatar and Oman have separately opened liaison offices in
Israel since 1995, but the two GCC states suspended the activities
of the bureaux in view of Israel's latest decisions on the
settlement construction.
</P>
<P>
Israel plans to build 6,500 homes for Jews on Har Homa in Arab
East Jerusalem, which the Jewish state captured from Jordan in the
1967 Mideast War. This move has triggered strong condemnation from
the Arab and Islamic world.
</P>
<P>
Muslims consider Jerusalem the third holiest site in
Islam after Mecca and Medina in Saudi Arabia, and Palestinians
want East Jerusalem as the capital of their future independent
state.
</P>
<P>
The GCC ministerial meeting called on Israel to back off from
the settlement decision and any other step which could change the
demographic and geographic status of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
According to Kuwait News Agency reports from Riyadh, foreign
ministers of the six Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) states wrapped
up their 62nd meeting in Riyadh.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers of the six GCC countries -- Saudi Arabia,
the United Arab Emirates, Oman, Qatar, Kuwait and Bahrain --
called on the Arab and Islamic countries which have embassies or
trade offices in Israel to suspend ties with it.
</P>
<P>
They also appealed to the other countries to reconsider their
relations with Israel and adopt measures to bolster the stalemated
peace process and force the Jewish state to commit itself to
honoring the accords it signed with its Arab partners in the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Qatar and Oman are the only countries in GCC that have trade
relations with Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
