<HEADLINE> Nigeria Expresses No Interest in Who to Run </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria said today it is not
interested in who will emerge as the winner of the May election
in Liberia under a peace accord to end the country's
seven-year-old civil war.
</P>
<P>
"It is up to Liberians to decide who will be their leaders,"
Balarabe Tafawa Balewa, special envoy of Nigerian Head of State
General Sani Abacha who is also the chairman of the Economic
Community of West African States (ECOWAS), said in Abuja, capital
of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
What Nigeria is interested in is only the restoration of peace
to that country, he said, quoted by the News Agency of Nigeria
today.
</P>
<P>
Currently, three former faction leaders -- Charles Taylor,
Alhaji Kromah and George Boley -- are widely believed to be the
strongest among those running for presidency.
</P>
<P>
According to the envoy, ECOWAS leaders are determined to abide
by the May election timetable, a position which was reiterated at
the meeting of the foreign ministers of the ECOWAS Committee of
Nine on Liberia, held in the Liberian capital of Monrovia last
month.
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that the envoy's words seem to be ECOWAS'
reaction to the concern expressed by the organization's
peacekeeping force, known as ECOMOG, over the slow pace of
preparations for the election scheduled for May 30.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG Force Commander Major-General Victor Malu said in
Monrovia on Tuesday that all efforts must be made to ensure that
a free and fair election be held on time after the success in the
disarmament exercise and research of hidden weapons in Liberia.
</P>
<P>
Malu also allayed any fear of post-election violence or
fighting while assuring the ECOWAS authorities and the
international community that ECOMOG was in position to contain
and effectively tackle anyone who might lose the election and try
to cause problem.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the envoy reiterated that Liberian refugees abroad
willing to participate in the election would be encouraged to
return under a voluntary repatriation program of the United
Nations High Commission for Refugees.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that there are about 500,000 Liberian refugees
in neighboring countries, most of whom are in Guinea and Cote
d'Ivoire.
</P>
<P>
According to Malu, Liberian refugees in the two countries have
been returning in large numbers recently, encouraged by the
decision of ECOWAS allowing them to vote at home.
</P>
<P>
"With the peace process moving as scheduled, more refugees
would be encouraged to return to Liberia to contribute to the
reconstruction and rehabilitation efforts of the international
community," said the envoy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
