<HEADLINE> Road to Southern Sudan Opens for Relief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 26 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Operation
Lifeline Sudan (OLS) today announced that roads from northern
Uganda into southern Sudan are now open for the delivery of
humanitarian aid.
</P>
<P>
In a news release issued here today, the OLS said that two
World Food Program (WFP) trucks carrying 40 tons of maize are
expected to arrive in Yei, southern Sudan, on March 27.
</P>
<P>
Road access to the Yei area of southern Sudan has become
possible for the first time in many years following the capture
of Yei, Kaya and Morobo along Sudan's southern border with Uganda
by the Sudan People's Liberation Army (SPLA).
</P>
<P>
More than 16,000 people and some 1,000 prisoners of war in Yei
town are in urgent need of food and medicine as a result of the
recent fighting between the Sudan government and the SPLA, the
release noted.
</P>
<P>
The OLS pointed out that the U.N. Children's Fund (UNICEF)
today delivered a planeload of emergency medical and relief items
to Yambio, southern Sudan, where trucks are ready to transport
the supplies to Yei.
</P>
<P>
WFP staff in northern Uganda reported on Monday that two of
the largest Sudanese refugee camps with a total of 81,678
refugees had virtually emptied over the last week.
</P>
<P>
OLS is a consortium of U.N. agencies and more than 40
international and indigenous non-governmental organizations
working to provide emergency relief and rehabilitation for an
estimated 3.4 million war-affected civilians in southern Sudan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
