<HEADLINE> Egypt to Compensate Victims of Gulf War in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Minister of manpower and
Immigration Ahmed al-Amawi said today that his ministry will write
out checks compensating victims of the 1991 Gulf War throughout April.
</P>
<P>
The payment of the 58.3 million U.S. dollars will begin early
in May for 23,334 Egyptians who are to take advantage of the
first portion of the Gulf War reparations that has already reached
the Central Bank of Egypt from the United Nations Reparations Fund.
</P>
<P>
The victims are those who were forced to leave Iraq or Kuwait
during the period from August 1990 till March 1991 because of the
Gulf War, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
The total of the reparations overdue for Egyptians is up to 823
million dollars and the remaining amount will be delivered later
with the continuous Iraqi oil sales.
</P>
<P>
This move came within the context of the oil-for-food deal
concluded by the U.N. and Iraq in December to allow the latter to
sell 2 billion dollars of oil in six months to ease the impact of
trade sanctions imposed on Iraq for its August 1990 invasion of
Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
In line with the deal, 30 percent of the Iraqi oil sales are
to be paid to people who lost their life savings or jobs due to
the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
In the first stage, 32 billion dollars will be paid to those
who were forced to leave Iraq and Kuwait during the war.
</P>
<P>
The total of the reparations, estimated at 200 billion
dollars, will be paid out of the returns of Iraq's oil sales over
20 years.
</P>
<P>
Iraq will have access to about 1.3 billion dollars over six
months after funneling 30 percent to the fund for Gulf War
reparations and meeting other U.N. costs.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. fund is expected to take several years in examining
the papers of those who have demanded to be compensated for their
losses in the war.
</P>
<P>
In the 90 days till March 10, Iraq exported 52.3 million
barrels of oil worth an estimated 1.07 billion dollars, including
pipeline fees to Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
