<HEADLINE> GCC Regrets Over US Veto of UN Resolution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, March 26 (Xinhua) -- The six-member Gulf
Cooperation Council (GCC) today expressed "deep regret" over the
U.S. veto of a U.N. draft resolution barring Israel from building
a Jewish settlement in Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
In a final statement issued after a two-day meeting in Saudi
capital Riyadh, the foreign ministers from the GCC states
expressed "deep regret over the U.S. veto against (of) a United
Nations Security Council draft resolution denouncing Israel's
internationally-condemned actions in East Jerusalem."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. twice vetoed the U.N. draft resolution demanding
Israel to stop building the new settlement in East Jerusalem
separately on March 7 and 21.
</P>
<P>
In a dispatch filed from Riyadh, the Kuwait News Agency said
that the statement expressed the GCC countries' hope that the
U.S. government would "intensify efforts to resume peace talks on
all tracks" as it is a co-sponsor of the Middle East peace
process and a friend of the Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
Israel's plan to build 6,500 housing units for Jews in Arab
East Jerusalem, which it captured from Jordan in the 1967 Mideast
War, has sparked strong resentment from the Arab and Islamic
world.
</P>
<P>
Most of the Islamic countries criticized the U.S. for biasing
toward Israel and adopting a double-standard policy, saying that
Israel's challenge to the international community would not have
reached such an extent without the U.S. support.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the GCC ministerial meeting asked Israel to back off
from the settlement decision and any other step which could change
the demographic and geographical features of Jerusalem, the third
holiest site of Islam where the Palestinians want to establish
their capital of an independent Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers of the six GCC countries -- Saudi Arabia,
the United Arab Emirates, Oman, Qatar, Kuwait and Bahrain --
called on the Arab and Islamic countries which have embassies or
trade offices in Israel to suspend their ties with the country.
</P>
<P>
They also called on the other countries across the world to
reconsider their relations with Israel and adopt measures to
promote the peace process and force Israel to commit itself to
the peace accords it signed with its Arab partners in the peace
march. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
