<HEADLINE> Albright </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 26 (Xinhua) -- The United States will not
change its hardline policy toward Iraq unless there are some
changes taking place there, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In a speech at Georgetown University, Albright reaffirmed as
long as President Saddam Hussein is in power, the Clinton
administration "will not change" policy.
</P>
<P>
"If past is prologue, under the current government, an Iraq
released from sanctions and scrutiny would pick up where it left
off half a dozen years ago," she said. "For these reasons, our
policy will not change."
</P>
<P>
Albright led the U.S. campaign against Iraq when she was the
U.S. ambassador to the United Nations from 1993 to last January.
Her speech signaled that her resolve remains unshaken now she is
the top U.S. diplomat.
</P>
<P>
"To those who ask how long our determination will last; how
long we will oppose Iraqi intransigence; how long we will insist
that the international community's standards be met, our answer is
as long as it takes," she said.
</P>
<P>
But she said the Clinton administration "looks forward" to the
day when Saddam is removed from power, a development that "could
lead to a change in U.S. policy." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
