<HEADLINE> Bank of Cyprus to Expand Business in Greece </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, March 26 (Xinhua) -- The bank of Cyprus, the island
Republic's biggest bank, plans to strengthen its presence in
Greece over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference here today, the Chairman of the
bank group Solonas Triantafyllidis said the Bank of Cyprus would
establish five new branches in Greece in the next five years to
bring the total number to thirteen.
</P>
<P>
The bank entered the Greek financial market six years ago and
currently employs a total staff of 300.
</P>
<P>
The priority of the bank development is to further develop the
private banking and to issue a visa card, according to
Triantafyllidis.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the operating profits of the Bank of Cyprus (Greece)
amounted to 4.3 billion drachmas (about 17.2 million U.S.
dollars), which accounts for 18 percent of the group's total
profits and marks a 37 percent increase over 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
