<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-26 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey to Grant 50 Million Dollars to Northern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Turkey would give northern Cyprus
50 million U.S. dollars for its economic expansion, according to
the semi-official Anatolia news agency today.
</P>
<P>
Serdar Denktas, son of northern Cyprus leader Rauf Denktas,
made the announcement after meeting with Turkish Deputy Prime
Minister and Foreign Minister Tansu Ciller in Ankara early today.
</P>
<P>
According to Denktas, this is part of 250 million U.S. dollars
to be granted to northern Cyprus in the light of a protocol
signed between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the disputed Cyprus issue, Denktas said that
northern Cyprus is working to achieve "a realistic and
sustainable solution" to this problem, adding that the most
important matter to contribute to the solution was economic
equality between the two parties of the divided island.
</P>
<P>
He noted that if the Greek Cypriots indeed wanted a lasting
solution to the protracted conflict on the island, the Turkish
side would be ready to hold any kind of discussions with
them.
</P>
<P>
The tension between the Greeks and Turks has persisted since
1974 when the Turkish government sent troops to occupy the
northern third of the island in the weak of an abortive coup by
Greek Cypriots seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, Turkey, the international supporter of
northern Cyprus, also threatened to launch a military strike
against Cyprus if it refused to stop its arms deal with
Russia for the purchase of anti-aircraft missiles.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's State Minister Abdullah Gul, after his talks with
Denktas, told the press that the government had ordered the
Eximbank and Ziraat Bank to start their operation in northern
Cyprus in an effort to help the northern part of the island
develop its economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
