<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study: TV Ratings Attract Young Viewers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 26 (Xinhua) -- A study shows that cartoons
and other children's TV programs in the United States rarely
depict the real consequences of violence, but often glorify the
attacker, and the new TV rating system is likely to attract
youngsters to restricted programs.
</P>
<P>
"Of all genres, children's programs contain the greatest number
of these high-risk violent portrayals," researchers from four
universities concluded in a report commissioned by the National
Cable Television Association.
</P>
<P>
The age-based TV ratings system went into use January 1. But
critics said that it does not provide enough information about
shows' violent and sexual content.
</P>
<P>
More detailed information about programs' violent, sexual and
language content would be more helpful to parents, they said.
</P>
<P>
"The type of rating system now being implemented has been shown
to attract many children to restricted programs," the report said.
"This may necessitate greater supervision of your children's
viewing, or it may be the source of increased parent-children
conflict over viewing choices."
</P>
<P>
the study found that nearly all the programs that depict
violence without real consequences or punishments and other
"high-risk" portrayals are cartoons.
</P>
<P>
Researchers worry that such portrayals teach aggressive
attitudes and behavior to young children.
</P>
<P>
"Of all channel types, child-oriented basic cable (Cartoon
Network, Disney and Nickelodeon) contains the most high-risk
portrayals for young viewers," the report said.
</P>
<P>
The number of shows containing violence aired by ABC, CBS and
NBC increased 54 percent this year from 47 percent a year ago, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
But the overall level of violence on both broadcast and cable
stayed about the same. This year the survey found that 61 percent
of programs contain violence. Last year, it was 58 percent.
</P>
<P>
The study was conducted by researchers at the University of
California at Santa Barbara, the University of North Carolina, the
University of Texas and the University of Wisconsin conducted the
study. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
