<HEADLINE> Clinton: Ross Has "Explicit Instructions" to Middle East </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 26 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton said on
Wednesday that he has sent chief peace broker Dennis Ross to the
Middle East with "explicit instructions" on how to get the
Palestinians-Israeli peace talks back on track.
</P>
<P>
During a photo session with Bosnian President Alija
Izetbegovic, Clinton said he dis so because he was "concerned"
about the peace process, which had again been derailed because of
Israel's decision to build a Jewish neighborhood in traditionally
Arab east Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Clinton declined to give any details about the "explicit
instructions", only saying: "We 're putting our heads together to
see what we can do."
</P>
<P>
It was said Ross' mission is to stop Palestinian strong
oppositions, which might evolve into violence, against obvious
violations by the Israeli government of Israeli-Palestinian
agreements.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli government defying world-wide criticism of its
decision to build 6,500 Jewish homes in east Jerusalem, has vowed
to push forward with its construction plans.
</P>
<P>
The United States, placating the Palestinians with some oral
criticism of Israeli decision, has twice vetoed U.N. Security
Council's resolutions condemning Isreal's construction decision.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week Secretary of State Madeleine Albright wrote a
letter to Arafat urging him to refrain Palestinians from taking
any violent actions against Israelis, tantamount to say the
Palestinians should sit by to watch Israelis doing whatever they
like in defiance of any peace agreements.
</P>
<P>
Ross is to seek, first of all, a clear statement from Arafat to
halt attacks on Israelis.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, a suicide bomber killed three women in a Tel Aviv
cafe and injured scores of others.
</P>
<P>
Ross will first meet Arafat in Rabat, Morocco, then fly to
Israel to urge Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu to ease
tensions. He will try to persuade Arafat and Netanyahu to open
negotiations over the future of the West Bank and Jerusalem.
</P>
</TEXT>
