<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economic Optimism Level in US Middle Atlantic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, March 26 (Xinhua) -- The level of optimism about jobs
and business conditions in the Middle Atlantic states of New York,
New Jersey and Pennsylvania soared over the last year at a faster
pace than any other region of the United States, a research report
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The study was conducted by New York-based Conference Board, a
non-profit business research group, which analyzed the region's
consumer confidence index basing on written surveys sent to 5,000
households around the country. The index is generally considered
the combined measure of residents' current economic outlook and
future expectations.
</P>
<P>
The Board said that in the first three months of this year, the
region's consumer confidence rose nearly 62 percent, compared with
the same period a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
despite the fact the the region continues to have the bleakest
perspective of any region in the nation, many more people
apparently now believe the better times ahead, the Board noted
</P>
<P>
The region's confidence levels are by far the lowest in the
nation. In March, for example, the preliminary consumer confidence
index for the Middle Atlantic region stood at 77.2, a level that
the Conference Board said is the rock bottom threshold for any
growing economy. Anything below 70 is considered recessionary.
One year ago, the confidence index for the region stood at 51. The
confidence index for the nation as a whole stands at 118.5, up
from 98.4 one year ago.
</P>
<P>
The Board attributed the higher optimism level in the region to
brightened job prospects triggered off by increased hiring on Wall
Street and the expansion of retailing, construction and film
making. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
