<HEADLINE> Signed Article On Dalai's Visit to Taiwan (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Anyone with some historical knowledge knows that the Dalai is
not an ordinary religious personage but a political exile who has
been long engaged in separating China overseas, the article
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The Dalai, once a religious leader in Tibet, has been in exile
overseas for 38 years since he failed in an armed rebellion in
Tibet in 1959 and fled to India.
</P>
<P>
The article noted that the Dalai has been engaged in activities
to split the country under the religious cloak for many years
under the support of some western anti-China forces. On the one
hand, the Dalai begged for outside help in an attempt to
internationalize the issue of Tibet. On the other, he plotted and
instigated riots in Tibet, thus becoming a satisfying tool in the
hands of Western anti-China forces.
</P>
<P>
The Dalai was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize in 1989. But as a
matter of fact, the article said, he does not seem to be a
"kind-hearted Buddha".
</P>
<P>
According to the "Chicago Tribune", the Central Intelligence
Agency of the United States trained many Tibetan exiles through
the 1960s and 1970s, who then sifted into Tibet and launched a
"guerrilla war" against the Communist Party of China.
</P>
<P>
In addition, news reports had it that the Dalai Lama and Shoko
Asahara, master of Aum Shinrikyo Sect of Japan, are "intimate
friends" and the Dalai had received "donations" from Shoko
Asahara.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
