<HEADLINE> Kazakhstan Produces First Jeep </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA-ATA, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Kazakhstan marked its entry into
the car market yesterday as its first jeep rolled off the assembly
line in a joint-venture with South Korea, the Kazakhstan Pravda
agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Attending the celebration ceremony were Kazakhstan President
Nursultan Nazarbayev, Prime Minister Akezhan Kazhegeldin and San
Hong, President of KIA, South Korea's second largest automaker.
</P>
<P>
It took only half a year for the Kazakhstan factory and KIA to
produce the first batch of jeeps since the cooperation agreement
was signed late last year.
</P>
<P>
The assembly line and parts for the first batch of cars
were all imported from South Korea.
</P>
<P>
The initial investment in the project was 600,000 U.S. dollars,
but will rise to some 20 million dollars when the factory is fully
operational.
</P>
<P>
Some 400 jeeps a month currently roll off the production line
and although cars parts are currently imported from South Korea,
Kazakstan will use up to 40 to 50 percent of its own parts
starting next year.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the project in Alma-Ata, KIA also plans to build
another production line in Aktyubinsk, another major city in
Kazakhstan. Most of the cars produced there will be exported to
countries of the former Soviet Union. 
</P>
</TEXT>
