<HEADLINE> Arab League to Open Office in Sarajevo Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Arab League (AL) Secretary General
Esmat Abdul-Meguid has expressed the league's readiness to open
an office in the Bosnian capital of Sarajevo soon.
</P>
<P>
Meguid, who made the remarks during a meeting here with visiting
Bosnian Prime Minister Haris Silajdzic, said he will refer the
issue to the upcoming AL Council meeting on Sunday, the Egyptian
Middle East News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Bosnian side hailed the opening of an AL bureau in Sarajevo
as an important step towards promoting relations between the
central-western Balkan country and the Arab states.
</P>
<P>
Bosnia also welcomes Egypt's endeavor to exert efforts in the
near future on the international arena to guarantee the full
implementation of the Dayton peace agreement, the same sources
said.
</P>
<P>
Silajdzic, who arrived here Monday on a five-day visit to
Egypt, has hailed Egypt's support for Bosnia-Herzegovina by
sending contingent to work with the UN peace-keepers and
multinational forces to monitor the 1995 truce agreement.
</P>
<P>
About 44 percent of Bosnia's population are Sunni
Muslims. During its 45-month civil war among the Muslims, Serbs
and Croats, about 250,000 people were killed and 2 million others
displaced. 
</P>
