<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Wipe Out Drug Problem: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 27 (Xinhua) -- China will take more effective
measures to "resolutely and completely resolve the drug problem,"
a senior official told a national anti-drug conference which ended
here today.
</P>
<P>
"The urgency and importance of this anti-drug combat must be
understood from the height of state security and national fate,"
said Ren Jianxin on behalf of the Central Committee of the
Communist Party of China (CPC) and the State Council.
</P>
<P>
Ren is secretary of the Secretariat of the CPC Central
Committee and secretary of the Committee of Political Sciences and
Law of the CPC Central Committee. His speech was made yesterday
and available today.
</P>
<P>
"The drug problem is not only an issue of public security, but
also a major political issue concerning social stability, state
security, and the destiny of the nation," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
"As a nation victimized by narcotics in past history, China
should never tolerate the prevalence of drugs, nor let the
humiliating history repeat itself," Ren said.
</P>
<P>
He demanded that the judicial bodies enforce the drug laws with
total compliance, and that the Party and government at all all
levels strengthen their leadership and control with the fight, and
arouse and rely on the masses of people to win the war against
drugs.
</P>
<P>
The strengthened leadership by the Party and government
organizations should be measured by how much they invest in the
anti-drug war to increase the police combat power, Ren said.
</P>
<P>
According to the anti-drug program outlined by the conference
for the next three years, China will strive to curb the increase
of new drug-using populations, block drugs outside its boundary or
at least seize them along the border areas, and to raise the
public awareness about the danger of drugs.
</P>
<P>
The conference was also told to make breakthroughs over the
next three years in the fight against narcotics-related crimes,
and with increasing efforts later, to completely root out the
drug-related crimes eventually.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
