<HEADLINE> S'pore Reaffirms Commitment to Keeping Close Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, March 27 (Xinhua) -- The Singapore Foreign Ministry
reaffirmed today the republic's commitment towards maintaining
close bilateral relations with Malaysia, despite inaccurate media
reports that Malaysia intended to freeze bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the Singapore Foreign Ministry said that as
Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong has said, Singapore would let
Malaysia set the pace and level of bilateral cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that Singapore had noted the statement by
Malaysia's Acting Foreign Minister that the press reports on a
freeze in relations between the two countries were not quite
accurate and that no decision had been made to freeze relations
with Singapore as the Malaysian newspapers had reported.
</P>
<P>
Singapore has also noted the comments of the Malaysian Prime
Minister in Tokyo that he did not think this is a major problem
and that naturally between neighbors there will be differences off
and on, but over time this feeling can be overcome, the spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
Local newspapers reported early today that the Malaysian
cabinet decided on Wednesday to freeze indefinitely all new
bilateral ties with Singapore in the wake of recent developments
following Senior Minister Lee Kuan Yew's remarks about the
Malaysian state of Johor being unsafe.
</P>
<P>
However, local television reported later that Singapore Prime
Minister Goh Chok Tong said that he wanted to understand the
Malaysian reaction first before further commenting on the issue.
</P>
<P>
He said that after signing a new air services pact with his
Australian counterpart John Howard, who arrived here last night on
a three-day official visit, his first as Australian prime
minister.  
</P>
</TEXT>
