<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Forest Fires Spread in Mongolia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Firefighters in eastern
Mongolia are battling to bring a series of forest and grassland
fires under control, newspapers here reported today.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 200 people have been mobilized to put out the fires
which are spreading quickly through Dornod province bordering
China's Inner Mongolia. More than 100 square kilometers of forest
and grassland in the province have been affected.
</P>
<P>
Altogether 11 forest and grassland fires have occurred in
Mongolia since late February in the western province of
Ara-Khangai, Dornod and neighboring Kehentei bordering Russia, and
the central province of Tov.
</P>
<P>
So far, there have been no reports of casualities or injuries.
</P>
<P>
A total of 417 fires swept 16 of the nation's 21 provinces
early last year destroying 10.5 million hectares of forest and
pasture land, causing losses of some 2 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
To prevent future disasters, the country's Special State
Commission has taken strict preventive measures this year, such as
prohibiting people and vehicles from entering forest land,
although dry weather and high spring winds are usually blamed
for the fires.
</P>
<P>
Fifteen percent of Mongolia, the world's largest land-locked
country of about 1.6 million square kilometers, is covered with
forest and 80 percent with grassland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
