<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Research Breakthrough Brings Hope to Diabetics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 27 (Xinhua) - A breakthrough in diabetes research
could mean the end of daily insulin injections for thousands of
sufferers, the science journal Nature reported today.
</P>
<P>
American scientists successfully "smuggled" drugs across
the body's powerful defense system by wrapping tiny drops of
insulin, which the body needs to control sugar levels, in spheres
of a few thousandths of a millimeter across.
</P>
<P>
These spheres of sticky polymer pass through the stomach and
stick to the walls of the small intestine, where they resist being
flushed away for several days. Eventually they penetrate the gut
wall and get into the blood. In this way, delicate substances have
been smuggled through the body's digestive juices.
</P>
<P>
Researchers, led by Professor Edith Mathiowitz of Brown
University in Rhode Island, say in Nature magazine that they were
able to alter the blood sugar levels of rats by giving them
insulin in this way.
</P>
<P>
Diabetics cannot produce insulin, which is needed to control
blood sugar levels.
</P>
<P>
To the scientists' surprise, they also managed to transfer DNA
with this method, raising the possibility of a new approach to
gene therapy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970327.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Farmers' Income-Increase Hits the Record High Since 1990 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 27 (Xinhua) -- In 1996 the increase of Chinese
farmers' income in real terms hit the record high since the
beginning of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
A latest survey conducted by the State Statistics Bureau shows
that the average net income of farmers in China last year was
1,926 yuan (some 240 US dollars), a rise of 22 percent or 9
percent increase in real terms than the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Experts attributed this to the rise of prices of agricultural
products and by-products last year, as well as the price control
efforts towards industrial consumption products.
</P>
<P>
The survey shows that the household production remains the main
source of income for rural residents. The income from household
production accounted for over 70 percent of farmers' total income.
</P>
<P>
The survey also shows that the Chinese farmers' average
per-capita income from individual labouring, in the form of
salary, last year was 451 yuan (55 US dollars), up 23.4 percent
over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey, the state policy of accelerating the
development of the central and western areas is attributable to
increases in farmers' income in those regions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
