<HEADLINE> Syrian, Lebanese Presidents Meet on Mideast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Syrian President Hafez al-Assad
met here today with visiting Lebanese President Elias Hrawi on the
latest development of the situation in the Middle East and
bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was attended by Syrian Vice President Abdul-Halim
Khaddam.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian-Lebanese talks aim to coordinate the stances of the
two countries towards the successive developments in the Middle
East, diplomatic source said.
</P>
<P>
Syria and Lebanon have reiterated that the two countries would
unite in dealing with the Israelis in the peace process. They
refuse partial and separate solutions to the issues with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Israel has been occupying the Golan Heights since the 1967
Middle East War and Syria demands its unconditional return. Israel
also established a 1,100-square-kilometer "security zone" in 1985 in
south Lebanon in a bid "to protect northern Israel from
cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Peace talks on Syrian-Israeli and Lebanese-Israeli tracks
suspended early last year. Lebanon upholds an adherence to an
interlock of the two tracks and refuses to talk any peace
settlement with Israel before a tangible progress is achieved
between Syria and the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Hrawi arrived here earlier today and his visit to Syria
coincides with the start of the U.S. special envoy to the Middle
East Dennis Ross's tour of the region.
</P>
<P>
Ross seeks to bring back to track the Palestinian-Israeli peace
talks following the deterioration of the relations between the two
sides due to the decision of the Israeli government to set up the
Har Homa settlement in Arab East Jerusalem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
