<HEADLINE> Budapest Aims to Become Conference Capital of Eastern Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Hungary is aiming to turn
Budapest into the international conference capital of eastern
Europe to attract high-spending tourists and delegates.
</P>
<P>
The Hungarian ministry of tourism said people who take part in
international meetings in Hungary spend much more than ordinary
tourists.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that international conference delegates spend
an average of 245 U.S. dollars a day, seven times more than
ordinary tourists.
</P>
<P>
They check in to five-star hotels, eat in expensive restaurants,
buy expensive gifts and ride around by taxi.
</P>
<P>
But these high-spending visitors only accounted for 0.3 percent
of foreign tourists in 1996, but brought in 169 million dollars in
foreign exchange, 8.4 percent of the country's income from tourism
last year.
</P>
<P>
Now, in a bid to attract more international conferences and
meetings, the ministry has decided to build more conference halls
and venues in Budapest over the next few years.
</P>
<P>
By 2002, Hungary aims to earn 1.5 billion dollars from hosting
international meetings, the ministry said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
