<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970327.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Advocates Eradication of Torture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 27 (Xinhua) -- China will continue working
towards the eradication of torture, by strengthening legal
systems, strictly enforcing the law and fulfilling its obligations
under the 1984 Convention Against Torture, the advisor of the
Chinese delegation to the 53rd session of the United Nations
Commission on Human Rights said today.
</P>
<P>
"It has been the consistent position of the Chinese government
to prohibit torture, or any other cruel, inhuman or degrading
treatment or punishment," said Dai Yuzhong, the advisor.
</P>
<P>
"In this regard, China has made unremitting efforts. As one of
the first signatories to the Convention against Torture, China has
strictly fulfilled her obligations under the convention and made
gradual progress over the past decade," he said.
</P>
<P>
Last May, the Committee against Torture considered China's
second report on implementing the convention. In that report, Dai
said, China gave a comprehensive account of its progress in
legislation, the judiciary and administration.
</P>
<P>
Last year, China's legislative body made major amendments to
the Criminal Procedural Law. On March 14 this year, the Fifth
Session of the Eighth National People's Congress adopted a
comprehensive revision of the Criminal Law.
</P>
<P>
"All these go along with the general direction of modern
criminal legislation. They stress the lawful punishment and
prevention of crime as well as the protection of the legitimate
rights of citizens," said Dai. "These constitute a major step
forward in the construction of China's legal system and are of
great significance in the prohibition of torture."
</P>
<P>
Talking about the work of the Commission on Human Rights, Dai
said, "The Commission on Human Rights has appointed rapporteurs
and established working groups, most of which can, within their
respective mandates, conduct research on relevant issues, exchange
their views and information and put forward useful suggestions.
</P>
<P>
"But we should not overlook the problems that still exist: A
few working groups and rapporteurs have deviated from their
mandates entrusted by the Commission, making slanderous
accusations against developing countries and believing very biased
arguments," he said.
</P>
<P>
"They have launched willful attacks on developing countries with
disregard for the judicial sovereignty of signatory states and
confusing the demarcation between torture and the legal punishment
of criminals. A stop must be put to such a practice," he said.
</P>
<P>
As for the draft optional protocol to the Convention against
Torture currently being considered by a working group of the
commission, Dai put forward two proposals:
</P>
<P>
1. The Optional Protocol should clearly manifest the aims
and principles enshrined in the UN Charter, especially the
principle of respect for sovereignty and non-interference in the
internal affairs of other states.
</P>
<P>
These principles are the basic norms of international relations
and therefore should be followed in the field of human
rights. Only when those basic principles and norms are complied
with can activities in the field of human rights play a
positive role.
</P>
<P>
As the optional protocol will establish an entirely new
mechanism, which will be carried out on the territories of
signatory states, these principles should be particularly stressed.
</P>
<P>
2. Prior consent from states concerned must be obtained before
any visit is carried out. Such a visit must be based on respect
for the laws of the states concerned.
</P>
<P>
The states concerned should be allowed to express their
views. This is because the prohibition and prevention of torture
is essentially the responsibility of states and realized through
the measures adopted by them.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of a visit is to ensure better cooperation, rather
than creating confrontation let alone putting a state on trial.
The success of the visit relies on the cooperation of the
signatory states. Without such cooperation, it is difficult to
imagine that any visit can be carried out smoothly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970327.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Clarifies Its Stand on Ties with Singapore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"I have to make it clear that what was highlighted in most of
the local newspapers today is not very accurate," Abang Abu Bakar,
who is Minister in the Prime Minister's Department, said in a
statement issued by his office here.
</P>
