<P>
"What was meant is that the government is studying the
implications of the episode on bilateral ties with Singapore
following the statement by Singapore Senior Minister Lee Kuan Yew
on Johor," he said.
</P>
<P>
Today's newspaper reports and the Malaysian national news
agency Bernama yesterday quoted several ministers as saying that
the Cabinet yesterday decided to freeze fresh bilateral dealings
with Singapore in the wake of recent developments following Lee's
controversial statements about Johor.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad is away from the
country paying a four-day official visit to Japan and Foreign
Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi is also in Japan as a member of
Mahathir's official entourage.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's relations with Singapore will be back to normal as
soon as Malaysians got over their feeling of hurt and bitterness
caused by an uncalled for remark against their country, Mahathir
said in Tokyo today while commenting on yesterday's reported
Cabinet decision to cool off ties and put off fresh dealings with
the island republic, reports from Tokyo said.
</P>
<P>
In Singapore, meanwhile, Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong said that
he wanted to understand Malaysia's reaction first before he could
further comment on the issue.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
