<HEADLINE> Burundi Denies Involvement in Zaire Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOME, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Burundi military strongman Pierre
Buyoya denied here today the Zairean government's
charge that his country is involved in the conflict in eastern
Zaire.
</P>
<P>
He said at a news conference that Burundi has nothing to do
with both the warring sides of Zaire, adding that he even does
not know rebel leader Laurent Kabila himself.
</P>
<P>
But he added that he is pleased to see that the two sides are
willing to negotiate to resolve their problems.
</P>
<P>
The Zairean government has accused Uganda, Rwanda and Burundi of
sending troops to fight along with the rebels in eastern
Zaire. The three countries all deny the charge.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, the rebel delegation attending the
extraordinary summit of the Organisation of African Unity being
held here clarified that the Zaire crisis is not a problem
between countries, but a problem within Zaire. The rebel
delegates told reporters that nobody will break the territorial
integrity of Zaire.
</P>
<P>
Buyoya is now in the capital of Togo for the summit aimed to
find a negotiated settlement to the Zaire crisis.
</P>
<P>
The two-day summit will close later today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
