<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sweden Ready to Send Security Force to Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, March 27 (Xinhua)--Sweden is ready to send a
security force to Albania on missions to protect trucks and other
vehicles delivering emergency aid to the country which has been
swept up in a wave of unrest and violence since January.
</P>
<P>
Swedish Prime Minister Goeran Persson announced the proposal
after meeting his Italian counterpart, Romano Prodi in Rome,
according to the press here today.
</P>
<P>
The announcement marks a change in the line taken by Sweden
since Tuesday, when Swedish Foreign Minister Lena Hjelm-Wallen
said that she was sceptical of proposals to send Swedish police
officers to Albania where armed rebels have taken control of
several southern towns in protest against President Sali Berisha.
</P>
<P>
Explaining this change in policy, Persson said pressure was
increasing on Sweden and other countries to prevent Albania's
total collapse, he said.
</P>
<P>
A Swedish decision to send in a police unit would be
conditional upon a request for such assistance by the United
Nations, the European Union or the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe, he said.
</P>
<P>
The European Union relief mission arrived in Albania on
Wednesday to discuss how to help end the unrest in the
country. Six EU states have also sent a team of military experts
to prepare for a possible multinational security force to protect
humanitarian workers and planned aid shipments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
