<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Official on Macao Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Chen Ziying, deputy director of
the Hong Kong and Macao Affairs Office of the State Council,
voiced the hope here today that China and Portugal will increase
cooperation to settle the Macao question.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua, he said April 13 this year is the
10th anniversary of the signing of the Sino-Portuguese Joint
Declaration, which has settled the historic Macao question, and
set an example in dealing with some international disputes.
</P>
<P>
The Joint Declaration has been well implemented in the past 10
years, and both sides have made achievements in the negotiations
on the Macao issue through the Joint Liaison Group, he said.
</P>
<P>
It is two years and nine months before Macao will return to its
motherland, Chen said, adding that the Joint Liaison Group should
accelerate its work to settle issues, especially the localization
of the civil servants and law, as well as the official language
status of Chinese.
</P>
<P>
Chen went on to say that the Chinese side has always kept to
the Joint Declaration, hoping that the two sides will increase
friendly negotiations and cooperation in handling the Macao
question.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the issue of nationality, Chen said the Chinese
government has always held a consistent and definite stance on
this issue.
</P>
<P>
As there are Chinese residents and non-Chinese residents,
especially the Portuguese descendants, in Macao society, the
Chinese side advocates that the non-Chinese will freely choose
their nationality, either being Chinese or Portuguese, instead of
requiring them to be Chinese, he explained.
</P>
<P>
How to conduct this work will be subjected to discussion by the
Sino-Portuguese Joint Liaison Group, Chen added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
