<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-27 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel, EU to Sign Procurement Deals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 27 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) will
sign two key procurement agreements with Israel within the next
few weeks in order to reduce the trade gap, according to European
diplomats.
</P>
<P>
EU Counselor in Tel Aviv Michael Ryan was quoted by today's
Jerusalem Post as saying that the public procurement and
telecommunications agreements would help reduce Israel's trade
deficit with Europe, which stands at 6.7 billion U.S. dollars in
1996, 72 percent of Israel's overall deficit.
</P>
<P>
Israel will be the only world signatory of such a
telecommunications agreement with Europe and the sole nation in
the Mediterranean to sign a procurement deal with the EU, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
The agreements will give strength to the EU-Israeli trade
over and above the Government Procurement Agreement (GPA) of
the World Trade Organization, allowing Israeli access to
Europe's annual procurement market of 600 to 800 billion
dollars and a 25 billion dollar telecommunications sector.
</P>
<P>
According to the main procurement agreement, Israel will be
able to compete for national and local government and public
enterprise agency tenders. In return, rules regarding offset
provisions, local content and threshold limits governing Israeli
state tenders under the GPA will be relaxed for EU suppliers.
</P>
<P>
There has been increasing concern in Israel's Finance
Ministry about local bidders' alleged ongoing failure to win
government tenders offered by EU countries. Israeli industrialists
maintain that there exists a proliferation of non-tariff
barriers which obstruct Israel's exports to Europe.
</P>
<P>
In a recent meeting, Israeli Finance Minister Dan Meridor
admitted that he and his staff had to make a greater
effort to explain the opportunities available in Europe to
domestic industrialists. The belief in Europe is that the EU
is the most liberal market in the world, given the
individual interests of each member state.
</P>
<P>
The Britain-based Economist Advisory Group Ltd. was currently
compiling a report for Israeli Finance Ministry examining how
Israel's full exporting potential to the EU could best be
realized, the report added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970327.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing to Host 1997 International Clothing, Accessories Fair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 27 (Xinhua) -- The upcoming China 1997
International Clothing and Accessories Fair, the fifth in China,
is to be held here April 8-11, attracting participants from 25
countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
The fair aims to give a boost to the status of China's garment
industry by giving more publicity for its name-brand products,
promoting the country's renowned designers, and transforming
Beijing into a worldwide garment center.
</P>
<P>
Besides the performances and business activities, an evening
gala to celebrate the revolution in China's fashion industry as a
result of the country's 18-year opening-up practice.
</P>
<P>
A forum on the world's name-brand clothes will be set up to
further discussion on conforming China's garment industry to
international standards.
</P>
<P>
An international seminar will be held then by world-renowned
designers, expected to help China train designers by absorbing
overseas experience.
</P>
<P>
In addition to model and designer contests, fashion shows will
be staged to showcase domestic leading fashion houses and
designers.
</P>
<P>
Some fashion shows will be staged by the Hong Kong Trade
Development Council, others will feature Italian designs.
</P>
<P>
The fair since 1993 has helped bring in a large amount of
foreign and domestic trade for China's garment industry and
conducted a record 2.5 billion yuan of trade volume last year.
</P>
<P>
During the 1991-1995 period, China witnessed an annual 21
percent growth of its garment industry, and has led the world in
its annual garment production and exports since the year 1994.
</P>
<P>
China's garment industry scored a 25 billion US dollars worth
of export volume in 1996, an increase of 4.2 percent over the
previous year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
