<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Official Congratulates Completion of PLA Military Facilities in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Ambassador Zhao Jihua, Chinese
senior representative on the Joint Liaison Group (JLG),
congratulated today the smooth and punctual completion of four
military reprovisioning projects to be used by the People's
Liberation Army's (PLA) garrison in Hong Kong after July 1.
</P>
<P>
He was speaking at a completion ceremony held by the Hong Kong
Architectural Services Department for the four facilities -- the
Military Storage Facilities at Shek Kong Camp, the Joint Movement
Unit at Chek Lap Kok Airport, the Military Hospital at Gun Club
Hill Barracks and the Naval Base on Stonecutters Island.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador pointed out that the pragmatic and actively
cooperative approach adopted by technical experts from the Chinese
 and British sides has ensured a smooth completion of the
facilities, which cost a total of some 4 billion HK dollars (513
million US dollars) and took more than two years after the JLG
reached agreement on the use of military sites on June 30, 1994.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese side is satisfied with the qualities of the four
projects, which meet the functional and technological requirements
 it set out, he continued.
</P>
<P>
He thanked the Architectural Services Department, the Civil
Engineering Department, the Electrical and Mechanical Services
Department and the three contractors involved for the great
efforts they have made toward the completion of the projects.
</P>
<P>
Following the completion of the principal parts, there is still
 a lot of work ahead, such as afforestation, testing of equipment,
 he continued, voicing the hope that cooperation will be continued
 in the next few months so that the projects will be handed over
to the PLA garrison to the satisfaction of all the sides.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from China's Defense Ministry and Foreign
Ministry, the Hong Kong government and the contractors attended
the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The three contractors are the China State Construction
Engineering Corporation, Wang Chong Construction Co. Ltd. and Yau
Lee Construction Co. Ltd. 
</P>
</TEXT>
