<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southwest China's Province Trains Farmers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, March 27 (Xinhua) -- More than half of the farmers in
southwest China's Guizhou Province are now able to apply two or
three agricultural practical techniques to their work, as a result
of training programs offered by the local government.
</P>
<P>
So far, more than 40 million farmers have attended training
courses on practical techniques; of this group, some 13 million
took more than two courses.
</P>
<P>
Guizhou, an undeveloped province in the country, is known for
its hostile farming production conditions and unskilled
farmers. In some remote mountain areas, the old-fashioned
low-yielding farming method of slash-and-burn cultivation is still
in use.
</P>
<P>
To change this, the province has listed the training of farmers
as a high priority in its agricultural scheme in the next several
years.
</P>
<P>
The efforts have paid off: Guizhou now has more than 50,000
agricultural technicians of various levels. And more than 40,000
farmers have passed the exams for the "Green Certificate," given
to farmers who have learned certain farming techniques.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
