<HEADLINE> Target Set for Chinese Translation of HK's Legal Documents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 27 (Xinhua) -- The mammoth task of translating
Hong Kong's court documents into Chinese should be completed by
the handover, Hong Kong's attorney-general said here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
But Jeremy Mathews admitted that a glossary of English-Chinese
legal terms, which is needed as a reference guide in the future,
would probably not be finished by the time.
</P>
<P>
A bilingual Court Documents Unit was set up in April 1995 in
the Judiciary's Prosecutions Division of Hong Kong's Legislature.
By November the same year, all defendants in Magistrate, District
and High Courts were served charge sheets and indictments in both
languages, Mathews said.
</P>
<P>
More trials will be conducted in the Chinese language in all
levels to the courts, He predicted.
</P>
<P>
He had planned to add 11 additional posts within the Bilingual
Court Documents Unit to meet the demand to provide not only
bilingual charge sheets, but also summaries of facts, agreed
evidence and immunity documents for witnesses.
</P>
<P>
Since the enactment of the first bilingual ordinance in 1989,
261 bilingual ordinances and 1,031 pieces of bilingual subsidiary
legislation have been enacted, Mathews added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
