<HEADLINE> HK Government to Spend HKD 18 Million on Handover Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 27 (Xinhua) -- A sum of 18 million HK dollars
(2.3 million U.S. dollars) is to be spent by the Hong Kong
government on X-ray and metal detectors as security is being
stepped up for the handover celebrations and the World Bank
Conference this year, a top Hong Kong police officer said.
</P>
<P>
According to the Hong Kong's Commissioner for Police Eddie Hui
Ki-on, about 2,000 police officers are to be on patrol to provide
security for handover ceremonies at mid-night on June 30.
</P>
<P>
Guests would have to walk through metal detectors and their
bags will be put under X-ray machines.
</P>
<P>
"The metal detector and X-ray equipment will not just be used
for the handover. It will be used at other occasions like the
World Bank-International Monetary Fund annual conference," he was
quoted by today's local English-language newspaper Hong Kong
Standard as saying.
</P>
<P>
Of the 2,000 police officers to guard the ceremony site at the
Hong Kong Convention and Exhibition Center, 600 will be deployed
to protect visiting VIPs and 300 to search the venue.
</P>
<P>
The rest would be responsible for security in the area in and
around the Center and at the British garrison headquarters at the
Prince of Wales building in Central Hong Kong where a farewell
ceremony will be held on June 30, according to Hui.  
</P>
