<HEADLINE> More Grain, Foodstuffs to Arrive in Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Eight ships loaded with 250,000
tonnes of French and Australian wheat and 13,000 tonnes of rice
and foodstuffs are expected to arrive in Iraq in the coming few
days.
</P>
<P>
Local daily Al-Kadessya reported today that the Umm Al Qasr
port in southern Iraq is ready to receive ships loaded with
foodstuffs and goods under the Iraqi-U.N. oil-for-food deal.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Minister of Transport and Communications Ahmed Khalil
was quoted as saying that his ministry approved a detailed plan
to facilitate the unloading operations of the ships coming to the
Umm Al Qasr port soon.
</P>
<P>
A Chinese ship carrying 13,000 tonnes of rice arrived at the
Um AL Qasr port Wednesday morning, the first arrival of foodstuff
under the oil-for-food deal between U.N. and Iraq via sea.
</P>
<P>
The first batch of foodstuff arrived in Iraq by land through
Turkey on March 20.
</P>
<P>
Under the oil-for-food deal, Iraq is allowed to sell 2 billion
U.S. dollars of oil for an initial six-month period to buy food
and medicine for its people hit hard by the sanctions imposed in
1990.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council Sanctions Committee has approved 57
contracts from 359 contracts applied by Iraq to the
committee. 
</P>
