<HEADLINE> More Counties to Receive State Education Subsidy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, March 27 (Xinhua) -- An additional 32 counties in
China's poorest western regions will receive state education
subsidies beginning this year.
</P>
<P>
Some 390 million yuan (nearly 50 million US dollars) will be
poured into these counties, covering a total population of 9.15
million and with weak educational systems, according to a national
education meeting which ended here today.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1,396 schools scattered throughout Tibet, Xinjiang
and seven other western provinces or autonomous regions will
benefit from the program, according to the State Education
Commission.
</P>
<P>
China launched the "Compulsory Education Program in
Poverty-stricken Regions" in 1995. So far, 383 counties with a
combined population of 150 million in central China have received
state subsidy.
</P>
<P>
This educational campaign involves the biggest sum of central
government allocation since the founding of New China in 1949.
</P>
<P>
Officials said that the money will be used to build schools,
buy desks and other facilities, and aid poor students who cannot
pay tuition fees.
</P>
<P>
Girl dropouts will be targeted first for financial assistance,
officials said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
