<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore, Australia Sign New Air Services Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Singapore and Australia will
expand air services between their two countries as Prime Minister
Goh Chok Tong and visiting Australian Prime Minister John Howard
announced here today that the two countries have agreed on new
arrangements for air services between Singapore and Australia.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the agreement signed here today, the two
countries will see a 37.5 percent increase in passenger service
capacity for the airlines of both sides up to the year 1999.
</P>
<P>
The agreement also includes liberal arrangements enabling both
Singapore Airlines and the Australian airline of Qantas to operate
joint services with the airlines of their choice.
</P>
<P>
In addition, it involves an exchange of 5th freedom traffic
rights including open access for airlines of Singapore to New
Zealand and open access for Australian carriers beyond Singapore
to Europe.
</P>
<P>
Besides, under the agreement, freight opportunities will be
more than doubled from 4.5 to 12 B747 freight services per week,
enabling the Singapore Airlines to add a fourth regular scheduled
service to Sydney and Melbourne.
</P>
<P>
The Civil Aviation Authority of Singapore said that the new
arrangements will benefit Singapore Airlines and Qantas, which are
the only Singapore and Australian carriers operating the route for
the time being. Both airlines will be able to plan expansion of
services which will bring tourism and trade benefits to both
countries, it said.
</P>
<P>
Qantas currently operates a total of 54 services per week to
Singapore from Perth, Adelaide, Melbourne, Sydney, Brisbane,
Cairns and Darwin. Many of these services go on to Bangkok, Hong
Kong, Bombay, Frankfurt and London.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore Airlines, on the other hand, operates 46
passenger services per week from Singapore to Darwin, Cairns,
Brisbane, Sydney, Melbourne, Adelaide and Perth. It also operates
four B747 freighter services per week to Sydney and Melbourne, one
of which also carries exports from Perth, the CAAS said.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, passenger traffic between Australia and Singapore hit
a record of 1.9 million movements. There was also an increase in
freight traffic of 4.7 percent to reach nearly 100,000 tons, it
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
