<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Unfolds Plan on Accelerated Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Financial Minister
Abthony Ani has disclosed the government's plan for accelerated
social and economic development by the year 2000 in Lagos.
</P>
<P>
In his lecture called "Nigeria in the Third Millennium --the
Road to Social and Economic Development" at a forum organized by
the Nigerian Society of International Law on Monday, Ani unfolded
the government's seven-point program which includes:
</P>
<P>
-- The development of the steel sector;
</P>
<P>
-- Improvement of energy supply;
</P>
<P>
-- Increased funding of scientific and technological
activities;
</P>
<P>
-- The empowerment of rural population through the Family
Economic Advancement Program;
</P>
<P>
-- Attainment of an independent judiciary;
</P>
<P>
-- Improvement of educational and health care systems;
</P>
<P>
-- The expansion of port facilities.
</P>
<P>
Ani assured that the Ajaokuta Steel Plant which has cost the
country several billion U.S. Dollars and been under construction
since 1980s will be completed by 1999, adding that the government
has earmarked 600 million Dollars for the project.
</P>
<P>
"It is envisaged that before the third millennium bursts upon
us, the Naira (Nigeria's currency) will attain its true
potentials as a convertible currency of the ECOWAS (Economic
Community of West African States) region," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is only logical, given the natural advantage of Nigeria as
the economic locomotive of the region," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
