<HEADLINE> Hunt For Illegal Weapons Resumed In Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, March 27 (Xinhua) -- An islandwide search to flush out
 all the unlicensed firearms resumed today, according to a police
officer here.
</P>
<P>
The Deputy inspector General of Police M. Nizam today said that
</P>
<P>
according to police estimate, there are at least 1,500 of these
weapons to be collected.
</P>
<P>
The search for these firearms began a few days ago, but it had
to be suspended temporarily on account of last week's local
government elections.
</P>
<P>
Nizam said that a number of special police teams are deployed
islandwide and each of them is headed by a gazetted officer. A
total of 125 men are deployed.
</P>
<P>
The police teams will be send to various parts of the country,
especially to those areas where the firearms are suspected to be
hidden, he said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that instructions have been given to all the police
teams to arrest all those who possess unlicensed weapons.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, some 1,600 of these weapons have been surrendered.
</P>
<P>
The unauthorized firearms are those issued to politicians for
their protection by the former United National Party regime during
 the southern youth uprising, and not returned after the uprising
was suppressed in 1989.  
</P>
</TEXT>
