<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-27 10:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spokesman: Arafat Ready to Meet Netanyahu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) President Yasser Arafat is prepared to meet with Israeli
Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu to salvage peace, Arafat's
spokesman Marwan Kanafani said here today.
</P>
<P>
"Arafat does not oppose holding direct talks with Netanyahu if
they aim at salvaging the Mideast peace process and searching for
reasons behind the current crisis between the two sides," he told the
Egyptian MENA news agency today.
</P>
<P>
Kanafani, who accompanied Arafat during his one-hour stopover
early this morning at the Cairo International Airport, said a date
for this projected meeting has not been set yet.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli negotiations have stuck after Netanyahu
went ahead with the Jewish housing project, and a Palestinian
carried out a suicide bomb attack in a Tel Aviv cafe, leaving
three killed.
</P>
<P>
Arafat said Wednesday that he was prepared to meet Netanyahu so
long as the purpose of their meeting was to discuss peace and not
a public stunt.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's communications chief David Bar-Illan has said
Netanyahu would accept a summit with Arafat so long as the issue
of security topped the agenda. But Palestinians object to any
preconditions and say the two sides must talk about other issues
besides security.
</P>
<P>
On future vision of the Palestinian-Israeli negotiations,
Kanafani said that implementation of the final status of the
Palestinian-Israeli accord hinges on finalizing the transitional
phase.
</P>
<P>
"However, the Israeli policy in this respect gives no hope in
reaching the final phase," he added, referring to Netanyahu's
proposal to wrap up the final talks within six months and bypass
the obligations under the interim accords.
</P>
<P>
The transitional phase issues such as airport, harbor,
redeployment of Israeli forces and the refugees remain unsolved,
he said. "This makes negotiations with the Israeli side useless,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
Palestinians and Israelis have missed the March 17 deadline for
final talks, which will settle the sensitive issues such as
Jerusalem and Palestinian statehood.
</P>
<P>
Refuting accusations that the PNA incites clashes in the
occupied lands, Kanafani blamed the situation on the Israeli
government.
</P>
<P>
"We fight extremism and terrorism and if there is extremism in
the Palestinian streets it is also found inside the Israeli
government," he said.
</P>
<P>
Arafat had cut short his southern Asia tour and headed for a
Jerusalem Committee meeting of the Organization of the Islamic
Conference in Rabat, Morocco, to meet with U.S. Mideast peace
envoy Dennis Ross, who has embarked on a trip to the Mideast to
try to get Israeli-Palestinian talks back on track.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. official is expected to fly to Israel later to see
Netanyahu Thursday or Friday in a bid to arrange a direct
Palestinian-Israeli meeting at the top level. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970327.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Ready to Properly Solve Problems Between China and Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 27 (Xinhua) -- China values its good-neighborly
friendship and mutually beneficial cooperation with Vietnam, and
is ready to hold friendly consultations with it to properly solve
problems existing between China and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman Cui Tiankai made the
statement at a regular news conference here today.
</P>
<P>
In response to Vietnam's recent representations to the Chinese
side on sea explorations by a Chinese drilling ship in the north
of the South China Sea, Cui said that China holds the rights over
the continental shelf and exclusive economic zones according to
the international laws, including the United Nations Convention on
the Law of the Sea.
</P>
<P>
Consequently, he said, it is beyond reproach that this ship has
made normal explorations in the continental shelf and exclusive
economic zones claimed by China.
</P>
<P>
He said China has always held that problems and disputes
existing among countries should be solved through peaceful
negotiations, noting that China cherishes its friendship and
cooperative relations with Vietnam, and is ready to hold friendly
consultations with Vietnam, in order to properly solve certain
problems remaining between the two countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
