<HEADLINE> Syrian Media Express Pessimism on US Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Syrian official daily Teshrin
expressed pessimism about the results of U.S. efforts as long as
Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu procrastinates full
withdrawal from the occupied Arab territories.
</P>
<P>
In its commentary today on the occasion of the start of the
new mission to the region by U.S. special envoy to the Middle
East Dennis Ross, the paper said that the revival of the peace
process necessitates that the United States stress the importance
of implementing all previous accords and the land-for-peace
principle.
</P>
<P>
However, Ross is not going to stress such a thing, the paper
said, adding that Ross's efforts aim only to cool down the tense
situation and "urge the Palestinians to accept Netanyahu's
conditions in return for nothing from Washington or Tel Aviv."
</P>
<P>
Ross left the United States for Rabat, Morocco, where he is
expected to meet Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat this morning
before flying to Israel to see Netanyahu later in the day.
</P>
<P>
Ross's tour of the region follows the deterioration of the
Palestinian-Israeli relations and the suspension of the peace
talks due to the Israeli government decision to build the
Har Homa settlement in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. efforts will be of no avail as long as Netanyahu
procrastinates the land-for-peace principle, according to the
paper.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, local daily Al-Thawrah today accused Washington
of protecting the Israeli aggressive government.
</P>
<P>
"The veto is still brandished at any one who dares to oppose
Netanyahu's anti-peace settlement policy," it said, adding
that "the U.S. is still talking from time to time about peace."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
