<DOCNO> XIE19970327.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Uganda Couples Threats with Promises to Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 27 (Xinhua) -- President Yoweri Museveni has
offered an olive branch to the rebel Lord's Resistance Army (LRA)
by suggesting its leader Joseph Kony and his top aides to choose
a country to stay and wait for an amnesty.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, a governmental officer said that the Ugandan
President had formed a new strategy and set up more task forces
within the Ugandan army to quell rebels still fighting,
especially in the north and west.
</P>
<P>
It was the first olive branch held out by the government after
Uganda's three main rebel groups -- the Christian fundamentalists
LRA, the West Nile Bank Front (WNBF) headed by a former minister
of dictator Idi Amin and the Allied Democratic Forces (ADF) --
had suffered heavy military losses recently.
</P>
<P>
Museveni launched the suppression drive in mid-February and
went to the north to command the fighting himself.
</P>
<P>
The message was revealed by Martin Aliker, the State Minister
for Foreign Affairs, at a meeting with northern traditional
leaders of Acholi tribe on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Aliker, who was given an order by Museveni to contact with the
LRA rebels, warned in the north on Tuesday that the Ugandan army
would not spare Kony if he continues to fight the Ugandan
government.
</P>
<P>
Aliker disclosed that he has also been in contact with Otti
Lagony, a famous LRA field commander, through an emissary.
</P>
<P>
The LRA, which once had 13 detachments with more than 2,000
soldiers, has only three detachments comprising some 200 men each
in southern Sudan after losing battles recently, earlier reports
said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in the past three weeks, the WNBF which was once
active in the north-west, lost its bases in southern Sudan and
western Zaire due to offensives mounted by those countries'
rebels.
</P>
<P>
As many as 800 WNBF rebels were reportedly killed in an ambush
in southern Sudan on March 12 and most of WNBF leaders were
either killed or captured.
</P>
<P>
Juma Oris, the WNBF key leader, was said to have been wounded
and gone underground.
</P>
<P>
Local media reported Wednesday that at least 119 WNBF remnant
fighters fleeing to Zaire were handed over by Zairean rebels to
the Ugandan authorities.
</P>
<P>
Around the same time, Sudanese rebels captured secret files on
the collaborators cooperating with WNBF and handed them over the
Ugandan security authorities.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of WNBF rebels have been sued by the Ugandan
authorities.
</P>
<P>
In another development, Lt. Colonel Geofrey Muhesi, the 307
Brigade Commander in western Kasese district, said the Ugandan
army there is ready to talk to the ADF remnants currently hiding
in the Rwenzori mountains.
</P>
<P>
However, Muhesi said this is just a field command's initiative
and would not be contradictory to the govertnment's line of not
talking to the rebels.
</P>
<P>
"In this strategy we will be identifying individuals and talk
to them. We are not talking to ADF... Now we only want to help
them out of the bush and show them how to get food without the
risk of being shot at," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The ADF now has no structural command and those boys up there
(in the mountains) are only playing a bloody game of survival by
raiding villages for food," he added.
</P>
<P>
ADF had some 1,000 militiamen in November when it entered
western Uganda from its bases in Zaire to try to establish bases
in Rwenzori mountains.
</P>
<P>
Later, the ADF main forces were reportedly eliminated by the
Ugandan army in the west and its remnants were dividing into
small groups. Its bases in eastern Zaire were also destroyed by
Zairean rebels.
</P>
<P>
Now some ADF remaining groups have allegedly penetrated into
southwestern Uganda and harass local people, reports reaching
here said.
</P>
<P>
The three rebel groups have their objective of toppling the
Museveni regime, but now, people do not know whether they will
accept the government gesture of peace or not after suffering
defeats in the battlefields. 
</P>
</TEXT>
