<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kazakhstan's Population Declines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA-ATA, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Kazakhstan's population has
dropped by 280,000 to 16.39 million by January 1, 1997, compared
to the same period of last year, the latest official statistics
said.
</P>
<P>
Kazakh experts attributed the decline to increasing emigration,
which began after the collapse of the former Soviet Union in
1991. This reversed the trend of population growth in Kazakhstan
which lasted from 1960 to 1991.
</P>
<P>
Experts also blamed the growing number of aging population
for the falling demographic trends in Kazakhstan. In 1990, the
population above 60 accounted for 10 percent of the total, but the
figure has jumped to 12 percent at present and will rise to an
estimated 17 percent by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
They predicted that Kazakhstan's population, which will begin
to pick up from 2000, will hit 16.75 million by 2005 and 17.18
million by 2010, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Kazakhstan now has an urban population of 9.11 million, plus
7.28 million in the rural areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
