<HEADLINE> Lawmakers to Inspect Enforcement of Hygienic Food Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 27 (Xinhua) -- China's top legislature plans to
send inspectors to six provinces and municipalities to check on
how well the Hygienic Food Law is being carried out.
</P>
<P>
The inspection, to start later this month and continue through
May, will cover provinces or municipalities of Zhejiang, Jiangsu,
Beijing, Tianjin, Hubei and Hunan.
</P>
<P>
Other provinces, autonomous regions and municipalities under
the direct leadership of the central government were asked to
conduct self-examinations and to submit their self-assessment
reports to the National People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
The law-enforcement inspection tours are aimed at promoting the
correct and comprehensive implementation of the law and ensuring
the people have safe, hygienic food with enough nutrition.
</P>
<P>
The focus of the inspection will be placed on food for infants,
children and health foods.
</P>
<P>
In addition to overseeing the general conditions of the law
enforcement, the lawmakers will devote much of their time
reviewing the hygienic conditions of food manufacturers, dealers,
and the supervisional mechanism over food hygiene.
</P>
<P>
The top legislature promulgated a trial law on hygienic food in
1982, and enacted a formal one in 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
