<HEADLINE> HK TDC Opens New Beijing Office </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 27 (Xinhua) -- The new office of the Hong Kong
Trade Development Council (TDC) that will provide library and
computer services officially opened today in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
At the opening ceremony, Michael Sze Cho-Cheung, president of
the council, said the TDC's move into the new office signals a
milestone in the economic exchanges and cooperation between Hong
Kong and inland areas.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong TDC has newly set up a library and a computerized
trade network in the new office, in order to provide better
services to trade partners in inland areas.
</P>
<P>
The library will have in stock some documents concerning the
economic development of Hong Kong, the inland areas and the
world. Through the TDC's computer network, data of a large number
of Hong Kong companies, overseas trade partners, and enterprises
in the inland areas will also be accessible.
</P>
<P>
An exhibition center will also be set up in the TDC's new
Beijing office to display Hong Kong's good-quality products.
</P>
<P>
Victor K. Fung, chairman of the council, presided over today's
opening ceremony, which was attended by some officials from the
relevant departments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970327.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Henan to Strengthen Protection of Farmland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Central China's Henan Province,
a major grain producer in the country, plans to strengthen its
efforts to protect arable land.
</P>
<P>
The per capita share of cultivated land among farmers in the
province is only 0.07 ha, lower than the country's average.
</P>
<P>
The province has said it will increase grain output by five
billion kilograms by the year 2000, but the ever-decreasing
acreage of arable land due to the increasing population made the
plan difficult to implement.
</P>
<P>
The province has worked out a series of regulations and rules
to protect farmland. So far, the safeguarded area stands at some
seven million ha.
</P>
<P>
To further tighten its management on tillable land, Henan plans
to set up a foundation for farmland protection. Meanwhile, a
compensation system will be adopted to ensure that the acreage of
farmland in protection zones does not decrease further.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the province will reclaim wasteland and
recultivate idle land to make up for the possible reduction in
acreage. In the past two years, the province has reclaimed 24,000
ha of such land. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970327.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-27 10:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan to Start Export to Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian companies will start
exporting detergents worth 26 million U.S. dollars early next
month to Iraq in line with the U.N.-Iraq oil-for-food deal.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's news agency Petra reported today that Ghasan Azar,
chairman of the Modern Chemicals Company (MCC), said that his firm
will start dispatching 4,000 tonnes of soaps to Iraq early next
month.
</P>
<P>
The first shipment will leave Jordan in the first week of
April, he said. The remaining shipments will reach Baghdad over
the coming four months.
</P>
<P>
"As soon as we receive the U.N. message of credit, expected in
a few days, we will start exporting our products to Iraq," Azar said.
</P>
<P>
The message is a guarantee from the U.N. to the companies that
the goods will be paid by the U.N., not by Iraq.
</P>
<P>
MCC is one of the 10 Jordanian companies which received
U.N. permission to export soaps and detergents to Iraq. The
approved orders, from nearly 50 sent by Jordan to the Sanctions
Committee of the United Nations, are worth 26 million dollars. The
rest, still unapproved, are worth around 95 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The items include detergents, cooking oil and salt.
</P>
<P>
The oil-for-food agreement reached last December, permits Iraq
to export two billion dollars worth of oil to purchase food,
medicine and other humanitarian aid over an initial six-month
period for its 20 million citizens suffering from U.N.-sanctions
imposed in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, an Iraqi industrial team arrived in Jordan early
this week to discuss with Jordanian industrialists on
strengthening trade ties between the two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
