<DOCNO> XIE19970327.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Farmers Upholds Consistent Land Policy (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 27 (Xinhua) -- It's mid-March in northeastern
China, the time for spring planting. Shi Yongjin, a 48-year-old
farmer, is plowing in the field as he calculates this year's
harvest.
</P>
<P>
"I earned 2,500 yuan (301.2 US dollars) last year
growing wheat and corn, I figure this year it won't be too far
from that, and will be enough to meet the daily needs of my
family," said Shi.
</P>
<P>
When the leasing agreement he signed 15 years ago came to an
end just before Spring Festival season in early February, Shi
re-contracted the 0.4-hectare-farmland from his village.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 of Shi's fellow villagers have signed such
agreements with the Xiadahe village commission in Liaoyang county,
for another 30 years.
</P>
<P>
In the bigger picture, farmers in one third of the villages in
northeastern Liaoning Province have renewed their land-leasing
contracts so far, with the rest to do so by the year-end or early
next year.
</P>
<P>
Since the nation launched its industrialization drive only a
few dozen years ago, the basic livelihood of rural Chinese still
depends on the farmland.
</P>
<P>
To raise its land-use efficiency, China began abolishing
farming communes and moved to the household contract
responsibility system in the late 1970s, offering the state-owned
farmland for lease to the peasants, mostly for 15-year periods.
Fengyang County of eastern Anhui Province was the pioneer, and
by 1984, the practice has spread across rural China.
</P>
<P>
Agro-scientist Wu Bin said the new system prompted Chinese
farmers to work harder to make full use of the arable land, since
"the more high-yielding and better quality the crops, the more
money they will make."
</P>
<P>
"In this way, it jerked up China's grain output steadily in the
past decades, and helped continually improve the life quality of
rural Chinese," said Wu, who is also an associate research fellow
with the Academy of Social Sciences in Liaoning.
</P>
<P>
China produced a record 480 million tons of grain last year.
Meanwhile, the average annual income for rural residents rose nine
percent to 1,900 yuan (228.9 US dollars); the growth nearly
tripled that for urban people earnings.
</P>
<P>
As early land contracts started to expire in recent years, the
Chinese government declared its commitment, as early as 1993, to
keep to its rural land policy by prolonging the contract term by
another 30 years. And the real work began in 1995.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970327.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Farmers Upholds Consistent Land Policy (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Statistics from the the Ministry of Agriculture show that more
than half of the Chinese villages had renewed the former land
contracts by the end of last year. Again, the spearheading Anhui
has basically finished the job.
</P>
<P>
But problems also arose: people found it impossible to repeat
the former practice of equally dividing the farmland among
villagers, due to changes in the rural economic layout in the
past ten-plus years. While the number and size of small townships
have been on the rise, so has the rural population, and the arable
land coverage has only increased to a small extent.
</P>
<P>
Pointing to such difficulties, a national conference on rural
work early this year stressed that the renewal of land contracts
was an indispensable policy that is in accordance with the
development of the productive forces in rural China, safeguards
the interests of Chinese peasantry and makes possible a stable,
rural China.
</P>
<P>
The government then decided to abandon the past practice of
land distribution and stick to the former contract plan, by which
death of the aged and new births have no effect on how much land a
family can lease.
</P>
<P>
Chinese farmers fully approve of this policy: an official
survey indicated that at least 98 percent of the rural households
are willing to hold the land they contracted 15 years ago for
another 30 years.
</P>
<P>
Shi Yongjin said, "All the people in my village are keen on
contracting the land again."
</P>
<P>
A new step by the government also lifted a ban on land
sub-contracting for more efficient use of the farming resources.
As long as the land is reserved for crop-growing, the farmers may
get official permission to sub-contract the land they leased from
the village to other people.
</P>
<P>
"This may open the once self-sufficient rural areas to market
competition, push the farmers to market, and facilitate the
transition of rural economy to a modern scale management mode from
the traditional one of scattered household production," said Wen
Tiejun, a research fellow from the research center of the Ministry
of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Farmers have tasted the sweetness of the new policy already,
especially in top grain-producing provinces of Hebei, Shandong and
Anhui. By joining hands with fellow villagers, they raised the
labor efficiency by using modern agro-machines on an even greater
space of land and selling the grain in large quantities.
</P>
<P>
Just as Vice Minister of Agriculture Wan Baorui said, a new
round of farmland contracting pushed China's rural policy another
step forward while basically sticking to the existing one.
</P>
<P>
"It is not just conducive to a more efficient rural productive
force, it is very significant to China's grain production, the
coordinated development of the urban and rural economy and a rural
China in peace," noted the vice minister.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970327.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
