<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Leaves Cairo for Jerusalem Meeting in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) President Yasser Arafat left here early this morning for
Morocco to attend an Islamic meeting on the issue of Jerusalem
after a one-hour stopover at Cairo International Airport.
</P>
<P>
Osama al-Baz, Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak's political
advisor who met Arafat during the latter's stopover, said that
they discussed the topics the Palestinian leader will raise during
the meeting of al-Quds (Jerusalem) Committee which will open in
Rabat, Morocco, today.
</P>
<P>
The discussion also dwelt on issues on the agenda of the 107th
session of the Arab foreign ministers here on January 30.
</P>
<P>
Baz said the 6,500-unit Israeli Jewish neighborhood in Jabal
Abu Ghneim (Har Homa) in East Jerusalem would dominate the meeting
of the 22-member Arab League.
</P>
<P>
Arafat briefed Baz on the viewpoint the PNA will expound during
the two meetings and asked him to convey it to Mubarak, Baz added.
</P>
<P>
Baz made it clear that those meetings acquire special
significance as they take place on the heels of the Organization
of Islamic Conference (OIC) extraordinary summit, held recently in
Islamabad, Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
The president's advisor expected that the committee could
activate resolutions passed during this summit to back the Arab
and Islamic stance in face of Israel's settlement activities in
East Jerusalem, which the Palestinians claim as their future
capital.
</P>
<P>
A proposal drafted during the summit by the PNA, Egypt and
Saudi Arabia urges all Arab countries to freeze ties with
Israel. It will be presented to the Rabat meeting.
</P>
<P>
The proposal also called for a fund be established with a
capital of one billion U.S. dollars to save the Islamic holy
shrines in Jerusalem and defend the Arab residents of the city.
</P>
<P>
Clashes between Palestinian stone-throwers and Israeli soldiers
have entered the 7th day, culminated in last Friday's suicide bomb
attack in a Tel Aviv cafe, in which three Israeli women were
killed.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Mideast envoy Dennis Ross is expected to meet Arafat in
Morocco this morning before he flies to Israel to meet Netanyahu
on a mission to restart direct talks between Israel and the
Palestinians, which have broken down over a week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
