<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gas-powered Vehicles Test on Road in Chinese City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, March 27 (Xinhua) -- A car and a jeep, powered by
liquefied gas, have passed road tests in Tianjin, a port city in
north China.
</P>
<P>
The powertrains of the remodeled vehicles, jointly developed by
Tianjin Liquefied Gas Corp. and Australia-based Apollo Co., create
a duel power systems enabling the use of either gasoline or
liquefied gas. A magnetic switch allows the transfer from one
power system to the other.
</P>
<P>
Drivers attending the test said that the new energy can ensure
the driving speed of 150 kilometers per hour under normal
conditions.
</P>
<P>
Data of the road test show the clean, energy-efficient,
low-lost gas is also environmentally-friendly. The waste of carbon
monoxide in the auto exhaust can be reduced by 90-100 percent, and
sulfide hydrogen by 50 percent. No benzene or lead wastes will be
generated in the burning process, and the engine's noise level can
be lowered by 40 percent below the normal gasoline-powered
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Local sources believed the prospects of the new energy are
promising. Tianjin Liquefied Gas Corp., one development partner,
has already remodeled all the company's 40 vehicles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970327.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Campaign Curbs Paid News </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 27 (Xinhua) -- China has made big progress in
curbing paid news among journalists, a senior official from the
All-China Journalists Association announced here today.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua News Agency, he said that since the
country launched the campaign in late January, the association has
received 477 telephone calls and letters reporting journalists who
had abused their positions.
</P>
<P>
According to the letters and telephone calls, some journalists
had traded their reports for money, luxury gifts and
advertisement, the official said, adding that 286 cases have been
handled.
</P>
<P>
These cases were reported by government officials, factory
workers, college professors, and even journalists themselves, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
The campaign is applauded by the public, the official
said. Some people said that the work will help improve
journalists' morale and professional sense of ethics.
</P>
<P>
News organizations have been very cooperative in helping the
association handle the cases, and some journalists have returned
the gifts and money they illegally obtained.
</P>
<P>
The official said that the association will publish some major
cases in newspapers in order to make all journalists aware of the
consequences of such actions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
