<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-27 09:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian, Syrian Ministers Blame Israel for Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Ministers Amr
Moussa and his Syrian counterpart Farouq al-Shara today held
Israel responsible for the grave crisis facing the Mideast peace
process.
</P>
<P>
In a telephone interview with Egyptian Voice of Arab radio this
morning, the two ministers said that Israel's settlement project
in East Jerusalem contradicts with the international law and
relevant U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Moussa and al-Shara arrived in the Moroccan capital Rabat today
from Damascus, the capital of Syria, to attend the meeting of the
Jerusalem Committee of the Organization of the Islamic Conference
after Israel started to build a Jewish settlement in Arab East
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian top diplomat had accompanied Prime Minister Kamal
el-Ganzouri to Syria for two-days of intensive talks with senior
Syrian officials on the future of the faltering Mideast peace
process on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Certain measures are needed during the Jerusalem Committee
meetings in order to make Israel understand that peace and
settlement do not go together," al-Shara told the radio.
</P>
<P>
Moussa stressed the need to firmly confront the Israeli
settlement activities through Arab and Islamic diplomacy and carry
out the resolutions adopted at the recent Organization of the
Islamic Conference held in Islamabad, Pakistan, to freeze ties
with Israel.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian National Authority (PNA), Egypt and Saudi Arabia have
urged all Arab countries to suspend moves towards normalizing
relations with the Jewish state, a proposal to be presented to the
Rabat meetings to save Jerusalem, a holy city for Christians, Jews
and Muslims alike.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers also called upon the U.S. to play the role of
a fair mediator as the main sponsor of the Mideast peace march
which has been endangered by the Israeli policy.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Mideast envoy Dennis Ross will meet with PNA President
Yasser Arafat in Rabat today and Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu later in Jerusalem on a mission to restart direct talks
between the two sides that have broken down over a week.
</P>
<P>
Clashes between Palestinian stone-throwers and Israeli soldiers
entered the 7th day today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
