<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-27 09:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Deploys Tanks in Anticipation of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Israel deployed tanks today
around major Palestinian cities in anticipation of widespread
Palestinian rioting during Sunday's Land Day mass demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
The order to deploy tanks near the entrances to Palestinian
cities was given by Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai after
holding urgent consultations Wednesday night with senior
security officials on the current situation.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, troop reinforcements were also deployed along the
Green Line in order to prevent Palestinian violence. Mordechai
also ordered the continuation of the total closure on the
Palestinian territories of West Bank and Gaza Strip, which was
imposed following last Friday's suicide bombing in central Tel
Aviv that killed four people and wounded dozens of others.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai said that while Israel hoped to advance the peace
process with the Palestinian National Authority (PNA), it could
not do before the PNA was determined to combat terrorism.
</P>
<P>
In a move to escalate the current tension, Fatah Movement,
mainstream faction of the Palestinian Liberation Organization
(PLO) led by PNA President Yasser Arafat, has decided to stage
"powerful" demonstrations to mark this year's Land Day across
the Palestinian territories.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrations were aimed at protesting Israeli policies
to expand settlements, especially its move to build a Jewish
neighborhood in Har Homa in the disputed East
Jerusalem. Palestinian Council held a meeting Wednesday in the
West Bank city of Rmallah, north of Jerusalem, to coordinate the
protest plans.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Arab leaders have also planned to hold large
demonstrations across the country to mark Land Day in a show of
support for the Palestinians in their fight against Israeli
settlement activities.
</P>
<P>
Bracing for possible violence, Israeli police are also on
maximum alert. Public Security Minister Avigdor Kahalani will
consult with senior police officials tonight to discuss security
arrangements for the Land Day marches and demonstrations within
the country.
</P>
<P>
While Fatah called for peaceful demonstrations, the definition
of peaceful protests apparently included throwing stones and
fire-bombs at Israeli soldiers, moves that could trigger
bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
For the past week, Palestinian youths have been throwing
stones and petro-bombs in clashes with Israeli soldiers, who
fired tear gas and rubber bullets to disperse them. The clashes
did not escalate into major bloodshed mainly due to the efforts
by the Palestinian police who tried hard to separate the
protesters from Israeli soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Clashes continued Wednesday night in the territories. About
20 people were injured as Israeli soldiers fired tear gas and
rubber bullets to disperse stone-throwing Palestinian youths in
Ramallah and the Erez Checkpoint between Israel and the Gaza
Strip.
</P>
<P>
Palestinians have observed the Land Day since 1976 when six
Israeli Arab villagers were killed and dozens of others wounded
by Israeli police who opened fire to quell their protests over
Israel's expropriation of land. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
