<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Cuts Charges on Phone Calls in E. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 27 (Xinhua) -- The Kenya Posts and
Telecommunications Corporation (KPTC) has announced a 62 percent
reduction in tariffs for telephone calls within the eastern
African region.
</P>
<P>
KPTC Managing Director Jan Mutai said on Tuesday that rates
for calls from Nairobi to Tanzania's capital Dar es Salaam and
Uganda's capital Kampala would drop by 42.9 percent to 28 Kenyan
Shillings (about 0.5 U.S. Dollar) per minute from 49 Shillings.
</P>
<P>
He said his corporation had simplified charge bands to both
domestic and eastern African region.
</P>
<P>
The local calls will be charged at the rate of 1.17 Shillings
per minute, a 83.3 percent drop from seven Shillings per minute.
</P>
<P>
The radius for local calls had been increased from 30
kilometers to 60 kilometers, he said.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, a call from Nairobi to Nakuru which is beyond 60
kilometers radius would be the same in tariff as calls from
Nairobi to any parts of Uganda and Tanzania, he added.
</P>
<P>
The reduction follows an earlier cut on tariffs for
international calls which lowered by 33.3 percent since January.
</P>
<P>
Mutai noted that the new tariff structure was part of the
corporation's efforts to align its network to the emerging
worldwide trend toward simpler network systems.
</P>
<P>
"The objective is to create flexibility, reduce charge bands
and respond to technological changes that are making time the
basis of charging rather than distance," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan official stressed that the move was the
corporation's contribution toward improving the performance of
the East African Cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
