<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Launches Suzhou River Purification Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 27 (Xinhua) -- The water of the Suzhou River, a
tributary of the Huangpu River that runs through China's leading
industrial city of Shanghai, is expected to clear up thanks to a
river purification project that started today.
</P>
<P>
The 120-kilometer Suzhou River, known for its serious
pollution, is an important passage between Shanghai and inland
areas.
</P>
<P>
The four-week project includes the clearing out garbage and
timber along both banks of the river, removing litter and floating
oil on the water, and tearing down all the illegal buildings
alongs the riverbanks and planting trees in their place.
</P>
<P>
The purification task is one of Shanghai's major projects to be
launched for building a national-level clean city.
</P>
<P>
According to the municipal development plan, the river will not
only be used for containing flood waters, but also will become a
scenic spot after its environment is improved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
