<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Sees Growth in Foreign Trade of Technology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 27 (Xinhua) -- China's capital Beijing has seen
a rapid growth in the export and import of techonology over the
past few years, with the total trade volume valued at four billion
US dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
According to the statistics released by the Beijing Municipal
Commission of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation, the city
imported 2,998 items of technology last year at a total cost of
three billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the city's overall export volume of technology also
rosed by 350 percent from 1995 to one billion dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
"The city's total export volume of technology was still less
than 440,000 dollars in 1980. It develops so quickly," said Wei
Guo, director of the Commission's Foreign Trade Management Section.
</P>
<P>
The commission now has taken measures to help the city continue
its growth of exports of large complete sets of equipment and
machinery this year, Wei said.
</P>
<P>
Beijing received two big orders from Iran last year, one for
equipment and facilities for the Teheran subway project, and the
other for ships. Each of the two orders were worth 150 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Legend Company in Beijing, a giant Chinese computer
manufacturer, also sold a total of 20 million dollars-worth
computers and computer components to the U.S and Hong Kong last
year.
</P>
<P>
"The 4,000 new and high-tech enterprises in the Beijing New and
High-tech Industrial Development Zone, and the 4,000
foreign-funded ventures have turned out to be major players of
technological export," the official said.
</P>
<P>
About 3,000 major enterprises in the city have upgraded their
equipment and technology by introducing advanced know-how from
abroad over the past years, he said, adding that these enterprises
had started exporting their own technological items.
</P>
<P>
A technology trade fair will be held here within this year,
which is co-sponsored by Beijing and Hanoi, the Vietnamese
capital, to boost bilateral trade, Wei said.
</P>
<P>
Priority will be given by the Beijing Municipal Government to
help technology export projects obtain credit loans and refund
their taxes, and develop trade with Japan and other countries in
Europe and North America, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
