<HEADLINE> S. African Armed Forces Plan New Management </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 27 (Xinhua) -- The South African National
Defense Forces (SANDF)'s territorial headquarters, groups and
part-time forces would be restructured and streamlined to improve
their efficiency, local daily Business Day reported today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing an Institute for Security Studies seminar in
Pretoria yesterday, Defense Minister Joe Modise was quoted as
saying that new management processes at regional level would
follow amalgamation of command and management functions at
national level in the Defense Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Integrated structures, including a joint operations center
with army, air force, navy and medical services participation had
permitted abolition of several duplicate command echelons.
Savings were expected to reach 300 million Rands (68 million U.S.
dollars), he said.
</P>
<P>
Modise called for a conscious mind shift to banish racism from
military. The practice had been outlawed, but individual
incidents could still be expected and had to be countered, he
said.
</P>
<P>
New regiments with names that reflect a new sense of national
pride would formed soon. he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
