<DOCNO> XIE19970327.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Removes Water Hyacinth at Power Station </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 27 (Xinhua) -- As many as 500,000 tons of water
hyacinth that accumulated at the Owen Falls dam in eastern Uganda
have been completely removed, reported the Monitor today.
</P>
<P>
The last thicket of the weed was scooped ashore on Tuesday,
the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The weed jamming the dam has caused extensive silting of the
turbines of the dam's hydraulic power station, Uganda's sole
hydraulic power station.
</P>
<P>
The operation, launched by Ugandan Vice President Specioza
Kazibwe in August, was jointly sponsored by Uganda Electricity
Board (UEB) and the Ministry of Agriculture and undertaken by
mechanical means which cost 1.2 million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The government of the Netherlands offered 800,000 Dollars
while Uganda raised the other 400,000 Dollars.
</P>
<P>
UEB now intends to construct a barrier at an estimated cost of
400,000 Dollars to contain future flow of the weed to the dam
area.
</P>
<P>
The weeds are covering all bays of Lake Victoria, Lake Kyoga,
River Nile in Uganda and, to a small extent, Lake Albert, causing
a calamity in the eastern African country's social and economic
development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
