<HEADLINE> Guizhou Develops Animal Husbandry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Guizhou
Province is to accelerate animal husbandry development by
building meat cattle farms and importing stud bulls from
abroad.
</P>
<P>
Ninety-seven percent of the area in Guizhou is hilly land, and
the province has vast grasslands.
</P>
<P>
For this reason, the local government has placed livestock
production as a priority in its development plan for the next four
years.
</P>
<P>
It will increase the number of butchered cattle to one million
head and the number of butchered sheep to five million head by the
year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Guizhou will allocate 120 million yuan to import 40 stud bulls
and 10 cows from Australia in a bid to improve the quality of
local animals.
</P>
<P>
It will also build a number of large stations for storing the
frozen sperm of stud bulls as well as 500 improved cattle centers
and 10,000 ranches in Bijie Prefecture and Bouyei-Miao Autonomous
Prefecture of Qianxinan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
