<BODY>
<HEADLINE> TV Education Proved Efficient in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 27 (Xinhua) -- China will increase the use of TV
universities to serve the people's needs for life-long education.
</P>
<P>
TV universities share educational resources with the whole
society.
</P>
<P>
A total of 2.12 million people have graduated from TV
universities since 1978, which is 14 percent of all college
graduates during that time, according to a five-day national
working conference on TV university education that ended here
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
TV universities, founded on February 6, 1978, were designed to
establish Chinese open universities and offer remote education
through modern education methods.
</P>
<P>
The State Education Commission (SEC) concluded that the
teaching quality and economic returns of TV universities were
fairly good as shown by the assessment of the quality of graduates.
</P>
<P>
Delegates to the national working conference agreed that TV
university education has been recognized by all parts of China
and the international community.
</P>
<P>
TV universities have been an efficient provider of education in
remote areas. During the past two decades, tens of millions of
Chinese farmers have learned agricultural techniques by watching
TV.
</P>
<P>
Statistics have indicated that some one million people
throughout the country were TV university students or TV
vocational school students in 1996 alone.
</P>
<P>
The national working conference advocated more spending in
TV education on building audio-visual classrooms, computer
classrooms, electronic mail boxs, and system for answering
questions on line.
</P>
<P>
Heads of 44 TV universities and some officials in charge of
provincial education committees attended the conference.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
