<HEADLINE> Vietnam's National Assembly to Meet in April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's 9th National Assembly is
scheduled to start its last session on April 2 to assess the
country's development and pass a number of laws.
</P>
<P>
National Assembly Office Director Vu Mao told a press
conference this morning that the legislature's session will last
more than one month.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, he said, will review reports on the work of the
National Assembly, the president, the prime minister, the chief
judge of the Supreme People's Court, the director of the Supreme
People's Procuratorate, and on the implementation of the tasks of
national development between 1996 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
It will also look at the budgetary work, land use planning, key
construction projects of the capital and voters' opinion on
scheduled election of the National Assembly in July.
</P>
<P>
Another task of the session is to examine and pass five laws,
including the revised law on the election of National Assembly
deputies, the value-added tax law, the law on business income tax,
the commercial law and amendments to the penal code related to
corruption, child sex abuse, drug abuse and drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
Vu Mao said a nationwide election will be held on July 20 to
select about 450 deputies for the 10th National Assembly, which is
planned for opening next September. 
