<HEADLINE> ADB Provides Loans For Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, March 27 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank will
provide 330 million U.S. dollars for Sri Lanka in loans from 1997
till year 2000, official sources said today.
</P>
<P>
The funding will be used for developing irrigation, urban
development, low cost housing, and the development of roads and
the environment in the country.
</P>
<P>
The ADB has also pledged a further 12 million U.S. dollars for
the establishment of an advisory council to supervise the
implementation of the development programs of the government.
</P>
<P>
An agreement to this effect was singed following a three-month
visit by an ADB team which studied the economic and social
conditions in the country.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka began borrowing from the ADB in 1969. The bank's
operational strategy in Sri Lanka aims to reduce poverty and
unemployment through higher economic growth.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1996, Sri Lanka had received 78 loans from the
bank totaling 1.8 billion U.S. dollars. In 1996, the bank approved
two loans for Sri Lanka amounting to 44 million U.S. dollars for
emergency rehabilitation, a petroleum facilities project and a
North Central Province Rural Development Project.  
</P>
