<HEADLINE> New Acts Needed Before Local Polls, Government Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Representatives of local
administration bodies in Nepal have urged the government not to
hold the local elections until after the introduction of new
decentralization acts.
</P>
<P>
Two organizations of the country's local bodies, the
Association of District Development Committees of Nepal and the
Municipality Association of Nepal, Wednesday asked Prime Minister
Lokendra Bahadur Chand to present the decentralization bill in the
on-going parliament session.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the organizations told a press conference here after
submitting a memorandum to the prime minister that the government
reportedly was going to go ahead with the local elections without
even bringing the bill in parliament for discussion.
</P>
<P>
The upcoming local elections will be held to choose chief
officers and representatives for local administration bodies in
the country's all 75 districts.
</P>
<P>
The former government led by the Nepali Congress (NC) party
decided to postpone the elections, originally scheduled to
conclude by mid-April, till the end of June to wait for the
parliament's approval of the decentralization bill.
</P>
<P>
The new acts under the decentralization bill are expected to
give more autonomous rights to local bodies.
</P>
<P>
The local bodies' organizations argued that the process of
empowering local people and involving them in the governance would
be laid back for another term of five years if the elections are
held without the decentralization acts.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the main opposition NC party Wednesday also called
on the government to hold the local elections after the parliament
passes the decentralization bill.
</P>
<P>
Nepal's present coalition government led by Chand of the
National Democratic Party (RPP) took office two weeks ago after
the NC-led government resigned following its failure to win a
confidence vote in parliament.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
