<HEADLINE> Thai Export Grows 5.1 Percent in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's export posted 115.9
billion baht (4.6 billion U.S. dollars) in January, a 5.1 percent
rise over the same period last year, deputy prime minister Amnuay
Virawan said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after the monthly meeting of the Thai central bank's
exchange equalization fund on Wednesday, Amnuay, who is also
finance minister, said the growth rate was higher than originally
forecast by the central bank.
</P>
<P>
He said it was a positive sign for the recovery of the economy.
</P>
<P>
January's growth was attributed to a rise in the country's
exports of canned food, shoes, electronic products and electrical
appliances and furniture parts, according to the deputy prime
minister who is in charge of the country's economic affairs.
</P>
<P>
However, Amnuay stressed that it is too early to celebrate a
recovery, saying that exports in February might slow down again.
</P>
<P>
He also disclosed that Thailand's foreign exchange reserves
rose to 39.2 billion dollars at the end of February from January's
38.1 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Local newspapers said that Thai imports in January totaled
154.9 billion baht (6.2 billion dollars), an increase of 1.3
percent over a year earlier.  
</P>
