<HEADLINE> Santer Applauds Italy's Efforts to Prepare for EMU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, March 26 (Xinhua) -- European Union Commission President
Jacques Santer said today he had confidence in the efforts Italy
was making to qualify for the European Monetary Union (EMU).
</P>
<P>
"I have confidence in what Italy is doing to achieve the
objective of the single currency," said Santer at the opening
ceremony of an exhibition here on the single currency euro.
</P>
<P>
The EU commission president declined to speculate on which
countries might first qualify for the launch of the euro slated
for January 1, 1999. He said that the decision would only be made
in the spring of 1998.
</P>
<P>
"The commission has never considered the single currency as an
end in itself," Santer said, "but as an instrument of economic and
political development."
</P>
<P>
Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi has promised to take
"extraordinary and supplementary" steps to get the country's
budget deficit in line with the criteria for entering Europe's
single currency by 1999.
</P>
<P>
Italy will make efforts to lower its deficit to 3.3 percent of
its gross domestic product -- short of the 3-percent figure
required by the Maastricht Treaty, ensured Prodi during an
interview late last year.
</P>
<P>
Prodi's government has presented a 63-trillion-lira (41 billion
U.S. dollars) austerity package of new taxes and spending cuts
designed to bring Italy's deficit to within the rules for the
monetary union. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
