<HEADLINE> Indonesia Breeds 78 Kinds of Flora and Fauna </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 27 (Xinhua) -- A total of 78 kinds of Indonesian
flora and fauna are being bred by 167 breeders, including ex-situ
conservation institutions, such as zoos and elephant training
centers, a senior official said.
</P>
<P>
"We benefit from the country's flora and fauna by breeding
those that are marketable and profitable, such as the yellow
sandalwood and the arowana fish," Forestry Minister Djamaludin
Suryohadikusumo told a panel discussion on bio-diversity
conservation here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia has also designated 21.1 million hectares of
conserved areas in 35 national parks, 88 sanctuaries and 178
natural preservation sites across the country, Antara news agency
reported today, quoting the minister.
</P>
<P>
He said there are untapped potentials in the country's flora
and fauna that have yet to be discovered and explored.
</P>
<P>
Data show that Indonesia's bio-diversity includes 10 percent
flowers, 12 percent mammals, 16 percent reptiles and amphibians,
17 percent birds and 25 percent fish.
</P>
<P>
Djamaludin said that only 92.4 million hectares of the
country's 113 million hectares of forest land remain intact.
</P>
</TEXT>
