<HEADLINE> Clinton's Brazil Visit Now October 12-14 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, March 26 (Xinhua) -- United States President
Bill Clinton will pay a visit to Brazil from October 12 to 14 this
year, said presidential residence sources in this South American
country.
</P>
<P>
During his trip, Clinton will visit Brasilia (the capital), Rio
de Janeiro and Sao Paulo, the three biggest cities in the country.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's visit to Brazil will be the second stage of his tour
of Latin America and the Caribbean. The tour is divided into two
stages and was initially scheduled for April and May, but was
postponed to May and October to give the president time to recover
from an operation to his damaged right knee.
</P>
<P>
The Brazilian sources said the postponement of Clinton's visit
would mean a six-month delay in the resolution of the two
principal trade disputes between their two countries.
</P>
<P>
The first is Brazil's opposition to moving forward the date of
the creation of the Free Trade Area of the Americas (FTAA) to some
time before the year 2005. The Brazilian government believes that
accelerating the creation of the FTAA will prejudice the
consolidation of the South American Common Market (Mercosur) which
includes Brazil, Argentina, Paraguay and Uruguay.
</P>
<P>
The second dispute concerns U.S. restrictions on the
importation of 27 Brazilian products including steel products,
orange juice, chickens and textiles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
