<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ministers Expect ASEAN Economic Boom to Continue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 27 (Xinhua) -- An economic boom in the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) will continue up to
the year 2020 and will help eliminate poverty in the Philippines
and the other ASEAN members.
</P>
<P>
This was the vision drawn by ASEAN economic ministers during
their informal meeting in Cebu, the second biggest city in the
central part of the country during the past two days, the local
press reported today.
</P>
<P>
"The momentum of growth is so strong that ministers forecast
that ASEAN will be an All-Tiger Club before the year 2020,"
according to Philippine Trade and Industry Secretary Cesar
Bautista.
</P>
<P>
Bautista added, however, that member countries will have to do
their own hard work to realize the vision of an ASEAN composed of
economic powerhouses.
</P>
<P>
The ministers also believed that prosperity will narrow down
the wide disparity of per capita income of ASEAN countries, he
said.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the ministers discussed proposals for
sweeping away the remaining roadblocks to intra-ASEAN trade,
expanding their economic alliances to include finance and
services, linking their webs of growth-inducing infrastructures
like transportation and telecommunications, adopting common
standards for products, and negotiating as an integrated economy
with outside trade groups.
</P>
<P>
"ASEAN members have learned that high economic performance
would happen only if they talk and act together like musicians in
an orchestra," Bautista said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the ministers will endorse the "ASEAN 2020"
vision to the ASEAN Leaders' Summit in Kuala Lumpur in October.
The summit will mark the 30th anniversary of ASEAN.
</P>
<P>
At their informal summit in Jakarta last November, ASEAN
leaders requested their economic ministers to develop an ASEAN
vision toward 2020.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines,
Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
