<DOCNO> XIE19970327.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> North China Port City Springboard for ROK Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Investors from the Republic of
Korea (ROK) have flocked to Tianjin, a port and industrial city in
north China, finding a springboard there to China's vast inland
areas.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin now operates regular routes by sea and air to several
ROK destinations. In addition, the city's efforts to improve the
infrastructure, including north China's largest development zone
and a bonded area, also offer a favorable investment environment
to incoming ROK investors.
</P>
<P>
Nowadays, eye-catching billboards advertising ROK companies can
be seen along the city's prosperous commercial
streets. Korean-made consumer commodities, from electronic
appliances to lab papers, fill stores in the local market.
</P>
<P>
To date, investment in 717 ROK-funded enterprises has exceeded
the one billion US dollar mark. In 1996 alone, an additional 136
companies, mostly from the industrial sector, registered in the
city. Investment from ROK now ranks fifth among overseas source
countries and regions to Tianjin.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts considered the inflowing investment a strategic
move for ROK investors aiming toward China's vast inland areas via
Tianjin.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey indicates that ROK investment last year shifted
from the previous labor-intensive areas to more capital-intensive
fields. Certain key ROK corporations have designated Tianjin sites
as their overseas production bases.
</P>
<P>
Sources revealed that Samsung Corporation intends to put three
billion US dollars in Tianjin to erect an electronic industrial
park. The group has already clinched 11 deals in China, six of
which are in Tianjin. Samsung plans to set up China's largest
video cassette recorder plant at the park.
</P>
<P>
LG Corporation, another ROK multinational, leased 360 hectares
of land to form a home appliance production base. The initial
investment was 75 million dollars, of which the Korean side holds
an 80 percent stake. Eventually, the corporation plans to inject
420 million US dollars and turn it into LG's largest production
base in north China.
</P>
<P>
Yingchang Musical Instrument Co., a Sino-ROK joint venture with
an investment of 39.2 million dollars, is now China's largest
piano producer.
</P>
<P>
As the investment environment further improves, the cooperation
between Tianjin and ROK cities can be expanded to more areas,
according to local sources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
