<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Says Helsinki Summit Hardest Negotiation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
said in a radio address today that the talks with U.S. President
Bill Clinton in Helsinki summit was the hardest he could remember.
</P>
<P>
He said that Russia and the United States had great different
views on the North Atlantic Treaty Organization's eastward
expansion during last week's summit and admitted that they failed
to close the rift on the issue.
</P>
<P>
On the summit results, Yeltsin said the two sides reached
common grounds that NATO will not move its nuclear weapons onto
the territories of new NATO member countries, NATO's military
movements to the East will not threaten Russian security and a
document on Russian-NATO ties will be strictly binding.
</P>
<P>
They also reached consensus on the anti-ballistic missile
defense and the reduction of strategic weapons, the Russian
president said.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin stressed that the response to the NATO's eastward
expansion was important, but it was not the only side of Russia's
foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
He also said that his country will first develop and strengthen
the ties with its traditional partners. 
</P>
</TEXT>
