<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Promises to Push Military Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
said today he was determined to push ahead with military reforms
and pay back wages to soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin, in a message to the army, said he himself would
supervise the enforcement of reform plans in order to get the army
to take on a new look, the Interfax News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"I am taking measures to improve the situation and pay the
salaries of soldiers and defense ministry officials," he said in
the message.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the conscript-based army of at least 1.5
million soldiers would be streamlined into a professional, 1.25
million-strong force by 2000.
</P>
<P>
"We are restoring order to the army. The main priority is to
put an end to embezzlement, corruption and theft of materials," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin promised that all the guilty, privates and generals
alike, would be punished.
</P>
<P>
He said the most important task was to enact and enforce a
uniform management system, and establish a complete and stable
army command system for national defense and security. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
