<DOCNO> XIE19970327.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Says Troops Will Leave Bosnia on Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 26 (Xinhua) -- United States President Bill
Clinton told visiting Bosnian President Aliya Izetbegovic today
that U.S. troops would leave Bosnia in June 1998, as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
At their meeting in the White House, Clinton said much work had
to be done to implement outstanding provisions of the 1995 Dayton
Accord, which ended the 43-month Bosnian war.
</P>
<P>
"There will be an international security presence (in Bosnia)
for quite some time yet, during which time we have to work hard to
do as much as we possibly can to implement the Dayton agreement,"
Clinton told reporters before the meeting.
</P>
<P>
"There is a lot of very specific work to be done, that if done
and done right will make it possible for the nation to succeed and
for people to be brought back into a more constructive
cooperation...when we're gone," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
Izetbegovic said that before the troops leave, the peace
accord, civilian provisions in particular, must be fully
implemented.
</P>
<P>
A separate disarmament pact must be enforced and Bosnia must be
included in the Partnership for Peace program under which former
East Bloc countries cooperate with NATO.
</P>
<P>
He said there were big difficulties in implementing the
civilian aspects of the accord, which was a condition for
withdrawal of foreign forces next year.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the Bosnian president warned that war could break
out again if the civilian aspects were not addressed.
</P>
<P>
"If the civilian aspects of the Dayton agreement are not
implemented, its military results will be null -- as if they never
were. We could again have war," said Izetbegovic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
