<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State Commercial Bank Aspires Overseas Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 27 (Xinhua) -- The Shanghai-based Bank of
Communications, one of the nation's ten authorized channels for
overseas capital, has seen its overseas business leaping forward
in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The bank has started branches in Hong Kong, New York, Tokyo and
Singapore, opening two representative offices in London and
Frankfurt, according to the bank's PR official Zhao Kuan.
</P>
<P>
One of the four state-owned commercial banks in China, it has
already become the agent bank of 508 overseas banks in 76
countries and regions, Zhao said.
</P>
<P>
The bank's function as a conduit of overseas funds also has
received active play, raising 270 million US dollars in Singapore
and 12 billion yen in Japan through issuing bonds in the two
countries, the bank's PR official said.
</P>
<P>
The rapidly expanding overseas business has brought the bank's
foreign currency assets up to 30 percent of the total in 1996, and
the profit in hard currency also accounted for one quarter of the
gross amount.
</P>
<P>
Latest statistics show that the Bank of Communications realized
nearly 40 billion yuan in gross profit between 1986 and 1996, with
its assets valued at 397.883 billion yuan last year.
</P>
<P>
Its total deposits topped 251 billion yuan last year, against
the outstanding loans of over 179.1 billion yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970327.0253 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Sanwa Expects to Start Yuan Business in Late April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Japan's Sanwa Bank Ltd. plans to
start dealing in business in the Chinese currency in late April,
according to the president of the bank's Shanghai branch.
</P>
<P>
Preparing for Renminbi yuan business, the Japanese bank is
scheduled to move to the Pudong Shipping Building soon and open
for business again on April 14, said Yoshiaki Kawamata, the
president.
</P>
<P>
He told Xinhua News Agency that he hopes his bank can start to
deal in the Chinese yuan in late April.
</P>
<P>
Since late December, China has approved a total of eight
overseas banks to deal in the yuan on a trial basis in Shanghai's
Pudong New Area, an emerging financial and trade district
separated from the city proper by the Huangpu River.
</P>
<P>
As a qualification for the new business, the banks must
relocate their Shanghai branches to Pudong, though they are
allowed to retain a sub-branch in the downtown area, known as Puxi.
</P>
<P>
Kawamata said that he is confident in his bank's prospects in
business in the local currency.
</P>
<P>
The overseas banks can accept deposits from overseas-funded
enterprises registered in Shanghai and overseas individuals, and
can lend to Shanghai-based overseas-funded enterprises and Chinese
firms, according to rules set by the People's Bank of China, the
central bank.
</P>
<P>
The banks can officially start offering yuan-based business
only after passing examinations by the central bank dealing with
both the hardware and software.
</P>
<P>
Kawamata said that Sanwa is currently making preparations for
the new business, such as learning about the relevant rules and
regulations and establishing business ties with Chinese banks.
</P>
<P>
"We need to learn from our Chinese counterpart, as yuan-based
business is an entirely new field to us," he said.
</P>
<P>
Sanwa's Shanghai branch, established in May, 1991, will have a
staff of around 100 after its relocation to Pudong, up from the
current 80. The Japanese bank set up branches in 1986 in Shenzhen,
in the south, and in 1993 in the northeast city of Dalian.
</P>
</TEXT>
