<HEADLINE> Second European Mission Arrives in Albania for Relief Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, March 26 (Xinhua) -- A joint mission of European
experts arrived in Tirana Wednesday evening to prepare for a
planned multinational relief operation in this Balkan country.
</P>
<P>
The team, of about 15 people, included experts from the
54-nation Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe
(OSCE), the European Union (EU) and its Commission.
</P>
<P>
Apart from assessing the scale of a relief operation, the
European delegation, the second of its kind in two weeks, will
discuss with Albanian leaders ways to restore order in the country
and its possible cooperation with international financial
institutions in reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a team of EU military experts who arrived in Tirana
Tuesday have started to scout Albania in preparation for the
deploying of a multinational force to secure relief aid.
</P>
<P>
The OSCE member states have agreed in principle to send a
multinational force to Albania to escort relief teams, but failed
on Wednesday to agree to the mission's mandate.
</P>
<P>
The organization has earlier agreed to send a long-term
political mission to Albania, which has been rocked by protests
and unrest since January after collapsed fraudulent investment
schemes wiped many people off life savings.
</P>
<P>
Also on Wednesday, a team of representatives from the World
Health Organization, the United Nations (UN) Children's Fund and
the U.N. Development Program and U.N. refugee experts arrived in
Tirana to assess the situation for relief operations. The World
Food Program is also to be involved in the aid operation. 
</P>
