<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East Chinese Vender Leads West Xinjiang in Small Commodities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Luo Yin, a diminutive fellow in
his forties, has created an entrepreneurial miracle by linking
east China to northwest Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region via a
small commodities business.
</P>
<P>
Walking out of the Urumqi Railway Station, passengers will soon
see a tall building which is Luo's latest success: the Xinjiang
Commerce and Trade City, also known as the Zhejiang Yiwu Small
Commodity Wholesale Market.
</P>
<P>
Yiwu is Luo's hometown in east China's coastal Zhejiang
Province, and also China's largest small commodity wholesale
market.
</P>
<P>
As a teenager, the southerner was a vender, hawking his wares
in Guangdong, Shandong and Yunnan provinces. But he soon
discovered Xinjiang was virgin territory for small commodities,
and in 1980 Luo started his career as a pioneer in opening up the
small commodity market in Xinjiang.
</P>
<P>
In the early 1980s, Luo bought an unprofitable Xinhua Hotel
located along Zhongshan Road and transformed part of it into a
wholesale and retail market for small commodities. Public response
was good, and Luo's brainchild is now well-known in business
circles.
</P>
<P>
His activities also have helped to develop two other markets
nearby.
</P>
<P>
In the late 1980s, Luo set his sights on a hostel close to the
railway station and turned it into a market, which he designed
himself. He then acquired a hotel nearby, and soon a new
commercial center began to take shape.
</P>
<P>
Luo's contributions have aroused attention from governments.
Feeling the westward shift of China's economic development,
officials from his hometown Yiwu came to Urumqi and agreed with
their counterparts there to co-establish a large-scale commercial
center in between the hostel and the hotel.
</P>
<P>
Now, the Xinjiang Commerce and Trade City links the other two
markets and has more than 3,000 individual households, 80 percent
of which are Luo's fellow citizens from Zhejiang.
</P>
<P>
More local businessmen and consumers are also benefiting from
Luo's good fortune: he and his colleagues have donated over
100,000 yuan to charities, and for earthquake relief and funding
for some organizations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
