<HEADLINE> FAO Seeks Brazilian Participation in Trade Fight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, March 26 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Food and
Agriculture Organization (FAO) today invited Brazil, a large
exporter of agricultural products, to take part in a campaign
against trade barriers in the world.
</P>
<P>
The invitation was issued here by visiting FAO Director
General, Jacques Diouf, during his meeting with Nuri Andraus, the
vice-president of the Brazilian National Confederation of
Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Diouf said the FAO is willing to unleash a campaign to alert
the international community to the fact that worldwide exports of
farm products have been prejudiced by trade barriers erected by
some consumer countries.
</P>
<P>
Brazilian sources said Brazil's export of orange juice to the
United States had been highly prejudiced by the latter's
imposition of high import tariffs.
</P>
<P>
Giving details of the FAO campaign to tear down trade barriers,
Diouf said a program, known as Telefood, would begin on October 18
and 19 through a world television network. The objective was to
collect financial contributions to combat hunger in the
world. 
</P>
