<HEADLINE> Former Residence of Famous Minister To Be Renovated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, March 27 (Xinhua) -- Former residence, study and tomb
of Lin Zexu, an imperial envoy of official of the Qing Dynasty
government (1644-1911), are under renovation in east China's
Fujian Province.
</P>
<P>
Noted for commanding the burning of massive amounts of opium in
Humen in south China's Guangdong Province in 1840, Lin was born in
a wooden house and received education in a neighboring building in
Zhongshan Road in this capital of Fujian.
</P>
<P>
The two buildings, including rooms and corridors, have a total
floor space of 835 sq m.
</P>
<P>
In 1993 the site was rented to a foreign investor, which was
opposed by some 100 members of the provincial committee of the
Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC).
</P>
<P>
Two years later, the provincial government bought back the land
use rights at a price of 12 million yuan from the foreign investor
and allocated another two million yuan to renovate the site.
</P>
<P>
The Lin Zexu Foundation has received two million yuan from a
Hong Kong businessman who promised to donate four million yuan for
the renovation.
</P>
<P>
The renovation project, starting last November and expected to
be completed in the coming May, also includes such subsidiary
facilities as reception halls, public toilets, a parking lot and
green lands.
</P>
<P>
The city invested 10,000 yuan to renovate the tombs of Lin and
his wife, his parents, and his brother and his wife. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
