<HEADLINE> Colombian Official Proposes New Measures Against Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Colombia's Controller
General David Turbay today proposed a national front against
violence involving guerrillas, paramilitary groups and different
strata of civil society.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to Senate President Luis Fernando Londono Capurro
and Chamber President Glovanni Lamboglia Mazzili, David Turbay
proposed that the political forces should reach a consensus to
create a national front against violence so that there can be
lasting peace in the country.
</P>
<P>
David Turbay said that violence has caused 15 billion U.S
dollars of losses since 1990, twice the country's international
reserves. One serviceman and three guerrillas died every day
during the past five years.
</P>
<P>
"Can we still talk about winners while the civilian population
contribute five deaths every day during that same period?" the
official asked.
</P>
<P>
He argued it is useless to continue traditional discussions
about the effectiveness of military strategy or about spending on
the armed forces or over the guerrilla's unwillingness to talk.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the debate should focus on what the country
has lost in half a century of confrontations and on the interest
in seeking national reconciliation. 
</P>
