<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Menem Rejects U.S. Request to Reform Law on Medicine Patents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Argentine President Carlos
Menem has refused to modify the country's law on medicine patents
as requested by members of a U.S. congressional delegation.
</P>
<P>
Menem told the visiting U.S. legislators today that Argentine
laws are up to international standards, said Jorge Campbell,
Argentina's secretary of international economic relations.
</P>
<P>
Protection of medicine patents was a topic at the meeting in
the government palace earlier today between the Argentine
president and the U.S. delegation.
</P>
<P>
Campbell said the U.S. legislators accepted Argentina's efforts
to protect intellectual property rights "but it was obvious that,
for them, our law is inferior" to that of the World Trade
Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
The legislation on medicine patents will be "a permanent issue"
for discussion on the agenda of both countries, he added.
</P>
<P>
Menem asked the U.S. legislators for their cooperation to
remove the restrictions that the United States imposes on
Argentina's exports of meat, peanuts and tobacco.
</P>
<P>
In mid-January, the United States announced its decision to
suspend 50 percent of its "preferential treatment" granted to
Argentine exports to the U.S. market.
</P>
<P>
The sanction, said U.S. President Bill Clinton in a letter sent
to Menem at the time, was introduced because Argentina's patent
laws "do not offer effective protection for the investments" made
by U.S. pharmaceutical companies.
</P>
<P>
The Argentine government has estimated that the U.S. measure
could cost Argentina 10 to 12 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
About 500 million of the 1.8 billion dollars in merchandise
that Argentina exported to the United States in 1996 were granted
preferential treatment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
