<HEADLINE> Tianjin to Build Bohai Bay into Export Giant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 27 (Xinhua) -- North China's industrial hub
Tianjin has earmarked 350 square kilometers of land off the west
shore of the Bohai Bay to launch a coastal special economic belt.
</P>
<P>
The 1994 scheme had untile recently remained largely unknown,
according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
By 2003, when the municipal government expects the majority of
the infrastructure to be in place, the new area is expected
generate half of Tianjin's gross domestic product and exports.
</P>
<P>
With a large port capacity and a wide array of special economic
zones, the fledgling Tianjin new area will provide a convenient
"green channel" for conducting external trade, the paper quoted a
high-ranking official was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The official predicted that should the Bohai Bay rim economic
belt take off, Beijing and Tianjin will provide the thrust while
the Liaodong Peninsula and Shandong Peninsula lift th bay to new
heights.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin's middle-term plan is to build the belt into one of Asia's
finest industrial bases and the leading one in the region.
</P>
<P>
Last year, exports from the coastal new area surged 39.6
percent from 1995, statistics show.  
</P>
