<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Academic Journal Issued on CD </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 27 (Xinhua) -- A publication that covers various
fields of natural and social sciences appeared for the first time
on compact discs (CD).
</P>
<P>
The newly published electronic edition of the Chinese Academic
Journal will offer readers easy access to research documents and
other written materials, according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
A total of 3,500 journals have been sorted and compiled into
CDs by the National Optical Memory Engineering Research Center.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Academic Journal CDs cover industry, engineering,
agriculture, medicine science, health, culture, history,
philosophy, economics, politics, legal science, education and
social sciences. The electronic journals will be published
simultaneously with the paper publications.
</P>
<P>
Readers could learn how to search for documents on CDs in one
service week started from yesterday with over 500 document centers
and research institutions involved.
</P>
<P>
Some 10,000 scientists and researchers across the country will
keep on close watch on the index-searching demonstrations, told
Wang Mingliang, vice-director of the electronic edition of the
academic journal.
</P>
<P>
Wang was quoted as saying that the electronic publication will
advance scientific research, technological development and
information management in China.
</P>
<P>
China has over 8,000 regional academic journals and 10,000-plus
internal reference journals. These journals, however, have failed
to offer sufficient service due to high printing cost, widely
scattered dissemination, overlapping in content and outdated
management.
</P>
<P>
Wang said that the English version of the Chinese Academic
Journal on CDs will eventually be available overseas to promote
academic exchanges between China and other countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970327.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nicaraguan, Costa Rican Presidents Discuss Deportation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Nicaraguan President Arnoldo
Aleman and his Costa Rican counterpart Jose Maria Figueres met
here today to discuss problems arising from the possible mass
deportation of Nicaraguans from the United States.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents also studied the common position on
migration, economic and trade matters that Central American
presidents will take when meeting with U.S. President Bill Clinton
during his visit to Costa Rica on May 7-9, said presidential
sources.
</P>
<P>
Clinton will meet with the presidents of Guatemala, El
Salvador, Honduras, Nicaragua, Costa Rica and Panama during his
three-day trip.
</P>
<P>
Aleman said that migration is a common problem in most Central
American countries, especially in Guatemala and El Salvador,
therefore, rulers of those nations should take a common stand on
the matter.
</P>
<P>
He requested Figueres for his cooperation, saying his country
was in no position to receive thousands of Nicaraguans who face
deportation from the United States and Costa Rica.
</P>
<P>
The meeting between Aleman and Figueres, who arrived here today
and will fly to Honduras for a meeting with Honduran President
Carlos Roberto Reina later on the same day, was held at the
Pacific beach resort of Montelimar, about 65 kilometers from the
Nicaraguan capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
