<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deal Struck on Information Technology Products </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Forty-one countries and regions,
representing 92.5 percent of world trade in computers and
software, today concluded the Information Technology Agreement
(ITA).
</P>
<P>
Under this agreement of the World Trade Organization (WTO),
tariffs on about 200 information technology products will be
reduced to zero prior to January 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
Some ITA participants, however, were granted flexibility in
eliminating tariffs on a few products after the year 2000, but not
beyond 2005.
</P>
<P>
The information technology agreement was first reached in
principle among 28 countries and regions, representing 83 percent
of world trade in information technology products, at the end of
the first WTO Ministerial Conference in December, 1996, in
Singapore.
</P>
<P>
The conference hailed the implementation of the ITA as
contingent, and expected to expand the ITA participation to cover
90 percent of world information technology trade by April 1 this
year.
</P>
<P>
Thirteen more countries and regions have joined ITA since last
December.
</P>
<P>
World trade in information technology products amounts to 600
billion U.S. dollars a year, accounting for 10.2 percent of the
worldwide merchandise trade.
</P>
<P>
The ITA agreement covers six categories of products: computers,
telecommunication equipment, semi-conductors, semi-conductor
manufacturing equipment, software and scientific instruments.
</P>
<P>
It does not include consumer electronic goods.
</P>
<P>
The ITA participants agreed to start considering, on October 1,
the inclusion of additional technology products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970327.0275 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Film "Memorandum of Three Gorges" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 27 (Xinhua) -- China will film a TV documentary
about the Three Gorges Dam project, mainly to answer questions
raised by foreigners who have a limited knowledge of the huge water
control endeavor.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for China Central Television, which is jointly
conducting the filming with the Committee for the Construction of
the Three Gorges Project, told Xinhua today that the 12-part
program, "The Memorandum of The Three Gorges," will serve as
official documentation of the country's modernization history.
</P>
<P>
"There have been different views and voices, as well as
suspicions and worries, about the Three Gorges Dam, both at home
and from abroad. Some people still oppose the building of the
dam," he said.
</P>
<P>
To explain the project, the series will contain a great number
of facts that were previously unknown to the public, and examine
its status in the nation's history featuring many of the successes
and challenges to the project, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The program will focus on foreign audience's requirements, and
remove their suspicions," he said.
</P>
<P>
The documentary will explain why the project is enormously
beneficial to the nation and the people, and will have a profound
impact on the development of the Chinese economy, he said.
</P>
<P>
The program also will emphasize that the Chinese people have
the ability to complete the project, which is the result of
lengthy scientific research and assessment.
</P>
<P>
The dam, which will be used to control floods and generate
electricity, will be completed early in the next century.
</P>
<P>
Many people are still doubtful about environmental problems
that will be caused by the project, and are worried that important
historical sites will be submerged after the Yangtze River is
dammed.
</P>
<P>
Resettlement difficulties are another major issue; an estimated
one million people will be moved from their hometowns to make way
for the work.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that the documentary will reflect all these
concerns and explain that the positive impact of the project will
outweigh the negative one.
</P>
<P>
Four filming groups will come to the Yangtze Valley to complete
the series, which will be broadcast by the end of 1997, when the
river is dammed.
</P>
<P>
"The program will be a pure documentary. No special effects
will be used," the spokesman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
