<HEADLINE> Qinghai Confident in Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 27 (Xinhua) -- A high-ranking official in
northwest China's Qinghai province expressed his confidence in the
province's economic prospects in today's China's Daily.
</P>
<P>
"Undevelopment in the past indicates greater potential in
the future," Tian Chengping, governor of the province, was quoted
as saying.
</P>
<P>
He noted that supporting Qinghai's development are its own
inexhausitable natural resources, adding that improving its
economy by tapping those resources is the logical strategy for
Qinghai in its drive to catch up with the affluent provinces in
China's coastal and eastern areas.
</P>
<P>
Qinghai, a vast sparsely-populated area on the Qinghai-Tibet
Plateau, has the potential to produce hydroelectric power and to
exploit its salt lakes.
</P>
<P>
Three large rivers, the Yangtze, Yellow and Lancang rivers,
originated in the province.
</P>
<P>
Along the Yellow River's 276-kilometer length in the province,
13 large and medium-sized hydroelectric power stations can be
constructed. Total installed capacity is estimated at 110 million
kilowatts.
</P>
<P>
The first 400,000-kilowatt generators in Lijiaxia on the Yellow
River are already in operation.
</P>
<P>
Salt lakes are another important resource for Qinghai province,
Tian said. The province has 27 large and medium salt lakes, most
located in the Caidam Basin, known as the "treasure bowl" since
ancient times.
</P>
<P>
The exploitation of natural resources depends on adequate
funding, infrastructure and technically-trained personnels, said
Tian.
</P>
<P>
After many years of hard work, transport, communications and
energy sectors have seen steady improvements, paving the way for
resources exploitation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970327.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bosman Ruling to Cover Non Europeans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Every soccer player would be free
to transfer under the Bosman ruling so long as he plays in the
European Union nations, the sport's world governing body said in
Zurich on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
FIFA amended its rules to allow players of all nationalities to
move on free transfers, saying once they are out of contract, the
clubs they move to no longer have to pay a transfer fee.
</P>
<P>
Fifteen months ago, Belgian soccer player Jean-Marc Bosman won
a court ruling against his club, FC Liege, that it should not
receive a transfer fee because his contract had ended.
</P>
<P>
As the ruling caused mayhem in transfer dealings in Europe, it
only applied to players born in the 15 EU countries as well as the
three affiliated nations Iceland, Norway and Liechtenstein.
</P>
<P>
Now it has been widened to cover players who are not from EU
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
