<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukrainian PM Dissatisfied With Agricultural Output </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Ukrainian Prime Minister Pavel
Lazarenko expressed deep dissatisfaction Wednesday with the
country's agricultural output.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the National Irrigation Seminar held in the Black
Sea port of Odessa, Lazarenko said Ukraine has the best irrigation
network in Europe, but its crop harvests have been slipping in the
past few years.
</P>
<P>
He blamed the harvest decline on state farm leaders, saying
they are more used to wait for government help than to help
themselves, ignoring that the country is transforming to a free
market economy.
</P>
<P>
Due to these inept officials, most of the 2.5 million hectares
of irrigated area have been wasted, complained the Prime
Minister. This caused tremendous losses for the country. Harvest
decreased by about 1 million tons in the southern provinces last
year.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine reaped 25.4 million tons of crops in 1996, a record low
in a matter of five years since Ukraine gained independence in
1991.
</P>
<P>
Lazarenko said the Ministry of Agriculture and Food failed to
become the engine to drive the agricultural modernization, short
of even explicit policies that can guarantee the reasonable use of
soil, fertilizer and technology.
</P>
<P>
"`Bumper harvest is the ground for economic stability of the
whole country," he stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
