Department of Trade and Industry that total investments to the
Philippines soared 20.2 percent last year to 490 billion pesos
(18.7 billion U.S. dollars) against 407 billion pesos (15.5
billion dollars) in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Today
</P>
<P>
-- The Philippine Central Bank Wednesday did the exact opposite
of the U.S. Federal Reserve and cut its overnight borrowing rate
from 10 percent to 9.9 percent and its overnight lending rate to
12.65 percent from 12.75 percent.
</P>
<P>
Manila Standard
</P>
<P>
-- While the Philippine government and the Moro Islamic
Liberation Front (MILF) Wednesday agreed to create an independent
committee to monitor violations of the interim ceasefire agreement
signed last month, another exchange of mortar shells between the
two sides was reported in Buldon, southwestern Mindanao.  
</P>
