<DOCNO> XIE19970327.0295 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany's Thyssen, Krupp Seal Steel Merger Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 26 (Xinhua) -- After one week's negotiations amid
mass demonstrations by steelworkers, Germany's two biggest
steelmakers Thyssen and Krupp-Hoesch this evening signed a
principle agreement to merge their steel operations.
</P>
<P>
If approved by the two companies' supervisory boards, the
merger will create Europe's biggest steel concern and the
fifth-biggest in the world with an annual output of 17 million
tons of steel.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement signed today by Thyssen boss Dieter Vogel
and his Krupp counterpart Gerhard Cromme, Thyssen would have a 60
percent stake in the joint steel company and take over its
management while Krupp-Hoesch would hold the rest of 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
Vogel and Cromme expressed the optimism that the merger would
create "a market-leading and highly efficient steel company".
</P>
<P>
Both companies also assured in the agreement that they would
refrain from major layoffs as a result of the merger.
</P>
<P>
But an official of the North Rhine-Westphalia state which
brokered the negotiations said earlier that about 7,900 jobs in
the two companies' steel units would have to phased out through
natural wastage in the next five years.
</P>
<P>
According to Wolfgang Clement, Economics Minister of North
Rhine-Westphalia, about 4,300 of the 7,900 jobs to be phased out
are directedly related to the merger. The remaining 3,600 have
been originally planned by the two companies before the merger
agreement.
</P>
<P>
Krupp's unprofitable steel mill in Dortmund will be the biggest
casualty of the merger. Its current workforce of 5,700 will be
reduced to 2,100 by the year 2002, Clement said.
</P>
<P>
Untouched by the announcement that their jobs would be safe,
steel workers of both Thyssen and Krupp continued their strikes on
Wednesday, with Dieter Kroll, who heads the works council of
Thyssen's steel unit in Duisburg, issued an ultimatum demanding
that the two companies present a written guarantee before April 7
to make sure that no one will be laid off as a result of the
merger.
</P>
<P>
"Otherwise, kettle will explode here," he warned.
</P>
<P>
According to a joint statement issued by the two companies this
evening, talks will be held with works council and trade unions on
how to implement the merger agreement.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
