<DOCNO> XIE19970327.0296 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 41 Participants Strike Deal on Information Technology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 26 (Xinhua) -- 41 participants, representing 92.5
percent of world trade in computers, software and other
information technology products, concluded here today the
Information Technology Agreement (ITA).
</P>
<P>
Under the ITA of the World Trade Organization (WTO), tariffs on
some 200 information technology products will be reduced to zero
no later than January 1, 2000 in a four-stage equal reduction of
25 percent per stage by July 1, 1997, January 1, 1998 and January
1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
However, Costa Rica, Indonesia, India, Korea, Malaysia, Chinese
Taipei and Thailand have been granted flexibility to eliminate
their tariffs on a few products after the year 2000 but not beyond
2005.
</P>
<P>
The ITA was first reached in principle by 28 members,
representing about 83 percent of world trade in information
technology products, at the end of the first WTO Ministerial
Conference held in December, 1996 in Singapore. A declaration then
provides that the implementation of the ITA is contingent on
expanding its participation to cover approximately 90 percent of
world trade in this sector by April 1, 1997. Since last December,
13 other WTO members have come on board.
</P>
<P>
Two more WTO members, the Philippines and El Salvador, have
indicated their intention to join in the near future.
</P>
<P>
World trade in information technology products is significant,
about 600 billion U.S. dollars annually, accounting for about 10.2
percent of world merchandise trade. There are six main categories
of products covered by the agreement: computers, telecom
equipment, semiconductors, semiconductor manufacturing equipment,
software, and scientific instruments. The ITA does not cover
consumer electronic goods.
</P>
<P>
The participants agreed that the first set of consultations on
additional product coverage would begin on October 1, 1997. These
consultations will be completed during 1998 with a view to the
entry into force of the revised schedules no later than January 1,
1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970327.0297 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Passenger Plane Giants Locked in Dogfight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, March 26 (Xinhua) -- The Boeing Company and Airbus
industrie, the world's two superpowers in passenger planes have
been locked in dogfight due to the bankruptcy of Netherland's
Focker N.Y. and the proposed merger of the McDonnell Douglas
Corporation with Boeing.
</P>
<P>
The focus of the marketing battle is on new orders over the
next 20 years which are estimated at one trillion or more U.S.
dollars. Industry forecasts suggest that more than 13,5000 planes
will be built to replace aging fleets and accommodate the growing
demand for air travel, particularly in heavily populated
developing countries.
</P>
<P>
When pressed for their definition of victory in this
trillion-dollar dogfight, Seattle-based Boeing, which has long
dominated the industry, wants to win two-thirds of all new orders,
about its current level. Airbus, a private held consortium of
manufacturers from Britain, France, Germany and Spain wants to win
about half of all orders. That would represent a big jump for
Airbus, which is less than half of the size of Boeing.
</P>
<P>
Clearly, only one company will succeed in its goal, and at the
expense of the other.
</P>
<P>
Over the last five years, Boeing has won 63 percent of the
plane orders, while Airbus has won 27 percent. In the last year
alone, however, Boeing won 66 percent of the orders and Airbus
received 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
Airbus hopes to leapfrog over Boeing in jumbo-jet sales by
building a double-decker plane that could hold more than 550
passengers. Airbus believes that there is enough demand to develop
its jumbo double-decker plane, which could hold about 120 more
passengers than the largest Boeing 747 model.
</P>
<P>
And Boeing, with the combined resources, revenues and future
profits from its acquisition of Mcdonnel Douglas, will have
enormous budget for research and development. It has introduced
its newest offering, 777, the larger version of 747.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the two giants are conducting propaganda campaign
against each other. One Airbus marketing brochure depicts a Boeing
777 as an aging stretch limousine painted taxicab yellow and
Airbus A340 as sleek Mercedes sedan. And in a brochure from
Boeing, Airbus is not even granted the respect of being mentioned
by name.
</P>
<P>
But for the two, what is more important is to lure customers.
Airline orders are typically measured in billions of dollars, so a
lot rides on each sale. In the last four months, Boeing has signed
long-term exclusive buying deals with American Airlines and Delta,
while Airbus has signed a larger deal with U.S. Airways. If a
customer is lost, it might be lost for a very long time.
</P>
<P>
The battle is fraught with risks and uncertainties. For Airbus,
if demand for double-decker plane falls short of its projections,
it might have trouble. Boeing, meanwhile, may face difficulties in
digesting its planned acquisition of Mcdonnel Douglas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970327.0298 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Parts of New York Plan on Diplomatic Parking Unlawful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 26 (Xinhua) -- Parts of a New York City
plan on diplomatic parking may violate international law, the
U.N. legal office said in a report released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Generally the elements of the city program are clearly within
the scope of the host country's power to establish laws and
regulations governing the operation and parking of diplomatic
vehicles," the report said.
</P>
<P>
"However,... certain provisions of the program do not appear to
be consistent with international law."
</P>
<P>
It cited the city's plan to confiscate diplomatic plates from
vehicles which have been towed and to ask missions to surrender
the license plates of diplomats who fail to pay parking tickets on
time as possible violations of international law and agreements on
diplomatic immunity.
</P>
<P>
"In general, measures aimed at depriving a diplomatic agent of
the right to drive by withdrawal of license plates, registration
and other pertinent legal documents... are in contravention" of
agreements which the United States accepted when New York was
chosen as U.N. headquarters, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The report welcomed some of the guidelines, which were
announced New York city March 11 and which take effect next
Tuesday. Among the them are setting up a telephone hot line for
complaints, setting aside designated parking places for diplomats
and providing foreign delegations with a monthly report on unpaid
tickets.
</P>
<P>
It also said diplomats have an obligation to scrupulously
observe the laws and regulations of the host country and that
failure to do so reflects badly on the entire diplomatic and the
organization itself.
</P>
<P>
The report has been circulated among the 185 U.N. missions and is
expected to be discused later by a committee which handles relations
with the U.S. government.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
