<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Proposes Two-week Renewal for Peacekeepers in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 26 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan recommended on Wednesday a two-week renewal of the U.N.
peacekeeping force in Angola in order to pressure the former rebel
leader into fulfilling the last of his commitments under a peace
plan.
</P>
<P>
The mandate for the 6,500-member force, currently the largest
U.N. peacekeeping mission, expires Monday. U.N. officials have
been frustrated by the refusal of former rebel leader Jonas
Savimbi to fulfill promises to create a new government of national
unity.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, however, Annan secured a promise from Savimbi to
send officials from his National Union for the Total Independence
of Angola, or UNITA, to the Angolan capital of Luanda to set a
date to inaugurate a power-sharing government.
</P>
<P>
But Savimbi has made similar promises in the past, only to
stall on implementing them. As a result, Annan recommended in a
report to the council that it extend the mandate for the U.N.
operation until April 15 because of uncertainties over the exact
date for the inauguration.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations brokered the 1994 peace deal between UNITA and
the government, ending two decades of civil war which erupted after
Portugal withdrew from the former colony.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
